1. Z0 {The history of the Belgrade Gambit begins on the day the history of Austria ended (!) for a (very dark) moment in time. According to information available online and in my database, Belgrade Gambit was first played in Berlin (!) on March 12, 1938, between two masters of that era: Kurt Richter (German) and Albert Becker (Austrian) .   For history geeks, this might be an interesting coincidence as this was the day the Anschluss of Austria to Germany took place, i.e. essentially an annexation of Austria by you-know-who. Richter lost to Becker (who, despite being Austrian, later on, became the captain of the German national team and ultimately fled to Argentina after the Chess Olympiad in 1939) and purportedly never used the opening again. It was so close to being known as the German/Austrian Gambit…  Six years later, at a Belgrade chess club, young talented player Mihajlo Trajkovic found the Richter-Becker game in a German chess handbook entitled 'How Not to Play Chess'. Ironic. Trajkovic found the opening to have more merit than it was initially given, analyzed it heavily, and was responsible for its name and revitalization. What a smart man Trajkovic must have been!  Throughout the years, numerous grandmasters played the Belgrade Gambit with White, including Peter Svidler, Ray Robson, Evgeny Postny, and the living legend - Juan Bellon. Hungarian GM Gyuala Sax managed to draw with White against the one and only Anatoly Karpov.   These days, at the highest level, the Belgrade Gambit is mostly used as a surprise weapon in classical chess or a regular battering ram in rapid and blitz. As Hikaru Nakamura once stated: “This has been played by many strong grandmasters (...) at the upper levels it is playable, if Black knows what they’re doing (...) at the beginner level I think it’s a great opening. It’s very easy to end up in trouble very quickly if you don’t know what you’re doing (...) and even then it’s not so easy to play.   I think it’s very powerful, on the borderline of unstoppable.” I simply couldn’t agree more. With proper play (and often heavy preparation) , Black is OK. But this is the assessment of most openings these days. When caught by surprise, even a very strong player (including GMs) may easily get lost in the tactical mazes of the Belgrade Gambit. You will also enter this maze. However, by buying this course you will be equipped with a map, a flashlight, and a tank in case you prefer to smash some walls (no physical tanks provided but I hope you get the point) .  As far as my personal record in the Belgrade Gambit is concerned, it is arguably the only opening I have a perfect 100% score in over-the-board (tournament) games. Initially, I didn’t intend to play the Belgrade Gambit before the publication of this course not to reveal my analysis.   However, I changed my mind when taking part in the Polish Cup (a very strong rapid event in Poland) . I found myself in a must-win situation with white pieces in the last round of the elimination phase of the tournament against another titled player - I had to win the game to qualify for TOP16. Winning the game reassured me of the practical difficulties players with the Black pieces face in the Belgrade Gambit.   I have beta tested some of the lines suggested in the course on online games and my expectations were exceeded. I managed to win quite a few spectacular miniature games against titled players. Frankly, I also lost some of them in an equally shocking way, but this mostly happened when I forgot my analysis.   Simply learn the lines and you’re ready to face anyone and I mean ANYONE!} *


