1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 ({Statistically, after} 3. Nc3 {in this position, in over 90% of games, Black replies with} Nf6 {, which leads to the initial position of the Four Knights Opening.}) 3... Nf6 4. d4 {Similarly, at this point, in over 90% of games, Black captures on d4 with the pawn and then there's no turning back from the Belgrade Gambit! Hence, assuming e4 e5 Nf3 Nc6 is already on the board; you can be relatively certain to get a chance to use the knowledge presented in this course. Pretty sweet, huh?} exd4 {In this position, recapturing on d4 with the knight is absolutely the main continuation leading to very well-explored positions. However, it is not even remotely close to our intentions.   What are they, then? Long story short: in most instances, we will opt for some frenzy chess, hopefully creating mayhem in our opponents' positions.   In order to achieve that, a pawn or two will have to be sacrificed to create pressure on Black as quickly as possible with our active pieces. In some lines (when Black acts like a killjoy), we will attempt to get a positional plus without giving Black too much counterplay.   My idea for this course was that only White can have fun!} 5. Nd5 {This is the starting point of the Belgrade Gambit. According to information available online and my database, it was first played in Berlin on March 12, 1938, between Kurt Richter and Albert Becker (you can see the beginning of this game below). Richter lost to Becker and purportedly never used the opening again.   Six years later, at a Belgrade chess club, young talent Mihajlo Trajkovic found the Richter-Becker game in a German chess handbook entitled 'How Not to Play Chess'. Ironic. Trajkovic found the opening to have more merit than it was initially given, analyzed it heavily, and was responsible for its name and revitalization (see a sample of his contribution to opening theory below).   Throughout the years, numerous grandmasters played the Belgrade Gambit with White, including Peter Svidler, Ray Robson, Evgeny Postny and the living legend - Juan Bellon. Hungarian GM Gyuala Sax managed to draw with White against the one and only Anatoly Karpov.   These days, at the highest level, the Belgrade Gambit is mostly used as a surprise weapon in classical chess or a regular battering ram in rapid and blitz.   I believe this properly reflects the level of problems Black is typically presented with. Over the board, they could be solved by a strong player, given enough time. On the other hand, weaker players (even titled ones) might fail to find a way to safety, especially under time constraints. It is fair to say that objectively there are better openings for White after 1.e4 e5 . However, I believe that the Belgrade Gambit might prove to be a very good surprise weapon or a secondary opening choice, even in classical games, assuming you're not afraid of lively, entertaining positions where the evaluation is not always clear.   I, myself, have played this opening mainly in online chess (blitz and rapid). However, I managed to surprise quite a few titled players (including GMs) and win against them.   My over-the-board score is 100% (1 out of 1) so far, but this is mainly related to the fact I didn't want to show my analysis before releasing the course. The Belgrade Gambit generally appeals to creative players, who thrive when having initiative.   Its main drawback is that there is a couple of ways to equalize or even seriously attempt to get an opening edge. Black may also try to simplify the game to such an extent that playing for a win will be troublesome for White.   But don't you lose your faith! I believe that after going through all of the chapters, you will still find a few aces up your sleeve.   According to my database, recently, Russian GM Klementy Sychev tried to revitalize the gambit on a few occasions presenting fresh ideas.   In order to get a better sense of the development of certain ideas in the Belgrade Gambit, please go through the sample annotated games.   Besides this historical background, I feel I owe you a few words of explanation regarding our last move. The knight occupies a central post, and it's very good news already. In the majority of the positions, it will be a pivotal piece.   Please note that the pawn on e4 is abandoned - this will often be a theme. However, capturing it should result in White's tremendous lead in development, which is exactly what White is looking for.} ({Black has several options here:   A) d6 B) h6 C) Bb4 D)} 5. Nd5 {E)} Nxe4 {F)} 6. Nb4 {G)} Be7 {H) Bc5 Both pawn moves (options A & B), i.e. d6 and h6 are rather timid continuations (also known as 'a dog in the manger approach'), mostly aimed to ensure that white's bishop development to f4 (in case of d6 ) and g5 (in case of h6 ) will not be as powerful as we intend it to be.  Options C-E, i.e. Bb4 ,} 7. Nd5 {and Nxe4 are direct approaches typically played to refute the gambit or at least take the chaos on the board to the next level. You should be eager to see any of those continuations - we'll show the opponents the true meaning of Belgrade Gambit!  The remaining possibilities are very serious - F)} Nb4 {immediately challenges the pride and joy of our position, i.e. the knight on d5 , while G) Be7 and H) Bc5 simply accelerate the development.  Isn't it one of the purposes of the opening? Overall, the first four options are clearly the weakest. On the other hand, the remaining four are valid alternatives, and you should really be well-prepared for them when playing the Belgrade Gambit.  We will handle each and every continuation in a separate chapter.}) 5... d6 (5... d6 {Chapter A h6 Chapter B Bb4+ Chapter C Nxd5 Chapter D exd5 Bb4+ Bd2 Qe7+ Be2?! ( Qe2! Bxd2+ Kxd2 Qxe2+ Bxe2 Ne7 d6! cxd6? Nxd4 and White has a clear advantage. Unfortunately, the remainder of the game is missing, though Radojcic concurred that Trajkovic won a deservedly nice ending. In the post-mortem they discussed the gambit and its ideas in much detail. 1-0 Trajkovic-Radojcic First Belgrade Championship 1945). d3 cxd3 Bxd2+ Qxd2 Nb4 O-O O-O Bd1 Nxd5⩱ 0-1 Richter,K-Becker,A Berlin 1938. Nxe4 Chapter E Nb4 Chapter F Be7 Chapter G Bc5 Chapter H.}) *


