1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Be7 {A very logical move. Black focuses on quick development. The bishop's position is perhaps not impressive, but it does prevent Bg5 ideas.} 6. Bc4 {Other moves are certainly possible but this one appeals to me the most. What's more, Black is tempted to take the pawn on e4 , which leads to some spicy chess.} Nxe4 7. O-O {For a split second Black has coordination issues. The knight on e4 as well as the king on e8 mean a chance for creating tactical motifs along the e file. Black needs to castle as quickly as possible and retreat the knight. In the meantime, White will attempt to develop a powerful initative.} O-O 8. Re1 {Simple and strong, White needs to put immediate pressure on the e file. After} Nc5 {White has a few really attractive continuations.} 9. Rxe7 {In a practical game, this may easily be winning. It's possible to hold but it will require surgical precision.} Ne6 {The only move for Black. It's essential to trap the rook on e7 . The other benefit of having the knight on e6 is that it covers g5 .} 10. Bg5 {From now on, Black needs to play a series of 'only moves' in order no to lose.} f6 {The only move and certainly not an easy one.} 11. Bxf6 {The positions become more and more complex, but this is what White should play in order not to lose the rook.} gxf6 12. Rxh7 {White goes berserker mode, but the alternatives are much worse.} Kxh7 13. Nh4 {White is down a rook (sic!). But at the same time, White is about to use the queen and the light-squared bishop to coordinate a dangerous assault on the king. In the meantime, Black's queenside is just watching the game on kingside without participating in it.} Rf7 {Black needs to find this defensive move in order to improve the defensive setup. It's basically about increasing the control over the 7th rank.} 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Re1 {Another piece joins the action. White should look for Nf5 and Nh6 or Re4 ideas. It's a paradox but White does not need to attack hastily as Black has severe development problems.} Rg7 16. Nf5 Rg5 17. Qh6 {White threatens Nxf6 . It should definitely be allowed by Black.} Rxf5 18. Qg6+ Kf8 19. Qxf5 {White is 'only' down a piece, but the attack is on. The f6 pawn is about to fall which would be a sign of huge problems for Black. If needed, you will always have ideas like Re4 - g4 / h4 or Bd3 .} *


