1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 d6 {An extremely rare continuation (not only at the high level). Such a move is most likely to be played by someone surprised by the Belgrade Gambit and trying to avoid your opening preparation.   Nice try! Luckily, we anticipated that as well.} 6. Nxd4 ({Simple and efficient. Obviously, centralization of the next minor piece is very beneficial, but it is also important to keep in mind that the e4 pawn might be hanging in some lines. As a matter of fact, White already indirectly protects the e4 pawn, as taking it would lead to a completely lost position for Black. Now we will cover as many as five options for Black: A1: Nxe4 , A2: Nxd5 , A3: Bd7 , A4: Bg4 , A5:} 6. Nxd4 {and A6:} Be7 {.}) 6... Bd7 {This is certainly not the most ambitious move but it is in a way consistent with Black's strategy so far - solid play without taking unnecessary risks. Now we have 2 interesting alternatives: 7.c4 supporting the pride and joy of our position (my preferred choice), i.e. the knight on d5 or 7.Bc4 with swift development and activity.} 7. c4 {This is a reasonable continuation in case you feel like the more straightforward 7.Bc4 does not seem to promise enough advantage. The main purpose of this move is to change the character of the position and take the most of our central control. One of Black's main strategic remedies against the Belgrade Gambit is an exchange of the knights on d5 , which is often followed by massive simplifications. By playing c4 , we will get the additional possibility of recapturing on d5 with the c pawn. Hence, the pawn structure will not be symmetric and the arising imbalances should favour White.} Nxe4 {As usual, let's see what happens after Black captures on e4 .} 8. Nb5 {Hitting the c7 pawn, as usual.} Rc8 9. Qe2 {Who would have thought that pins are so powerful?!} f5 10. f3 Ne5 {A very cunning move! Now it is Black, who threatens to win a knight (by playing c7 - c6 ). Unfair!} 11. fxe4 c6 12. Nbc7+ Kf7 {This just doesn't look like a human decision. We all pledged to protect the king! Jokes aside, thanks to this move Black manages to win the knight back, but the open f file might give White nice attacking chances later on.} 13. g3 {As the queen is on e2 , it makes perfect sense to develop the bishop via the other diagonal.} cxd5 14. Nxd5 Rxc4 15. Bg2 Qc8 16. O-O {We need to finish development and castle as fast as we can. Please note that the connection of the rooks enables White to protect the bishop on c1 and start pressurizing along the f file.} Rc2 {The most forcing and aggressive approach. We were supposed to be the attacking party!} 17. Bd2 Qc5+ 18. Kh1 {This position is extremely complex. White is down a pawn but Black will find it difficult to finish development. If White manages to break through on the kingside, he should have very realistic winning chances. Perhaps Black should try something creative like h5 - h4 , introducing the rook into play. The engine claims significant advantage for White but remember to treat this position with due care. In reality, Black's position is just much more difficult to handle for a human.} *


