1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 h6 {This move actually makes some sense. Black is simply trying to prevent 6.Bg5 with the irritating pin. Yet, it is a rather rare choice for Black - at least at a higher level.   The great majority of this chapter originates from computer analysis. Still, it's worth learning these lines as they nicely present certain ideas, which we will use in other positions.   I don't recommend memorizing all of it. Try to treat this chapter as a unique chance to increase your resourcefulness.   When preparing this chapter, I didn't expect to find so many fascinating tactical and strategic ideas. Welcome to the Belgrade jungle!} 6. Bf4 {White develops the bishop, attacking the c7 pawn and threatening to score the point.} Bb4+ {It's always worth checking the strength of the most forcing continuations. However, this time Black shouldn't be so aggressive. The following sequence of moves is quite forcing and requires memorization.   In case you realize in the game that your memory malfunctions, make sure to look for dynamic moves that apply pressure on Black.} 7. Nxb4 Nxb4 8. e5 {Put your hands in the air and give me all your money! The Black knights are likely to wander around pointlessly.} Qe7 9. Bc4 {At this point, we will investigate d5 and d6 for Black. Both seem equally logical.} d6 10. O-O dxe5 11. Nxe5 Be6 {It's logical but rather dubious.} 12. Bxe6 Qxe6 13. Qxd4 {Black may very easily fall for a trap.} Nbd5 14. Ng6 {Kingdom for opening the e file!} fxg6 15. Rae1 {Black drops the queen.} *

