1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 h6 {This move actually makes some sense. Black is simply trying to prevent 6.Bg5 with the irritating pin. Yet, it is a rather rare choice for Black - at least at a higher level.   The great majority of this chapter originates from computer analysis. Still, it's worth learning these lines as they nicely present certain ideas, which we will use in other positions.   I don't recommend memorizing all of it. Try to treat this chapter as a unique chance to increase your resourcefulness.   When preparing this chapter, I didn't expect to find so many fascinating tactical and strategic ideas. Welcome to the Belgrade jungle!} 6. Bf4 {White develops the bishop, attacking the c7 pawn and threatening to score the point.} Nxd5 {This move could be treated as the mainline of 5... h6 . From Black's perspective, it makes a lot of sense to take on d5 in order to develop the bishop to b4 and, later on, the queen to e7 . A very tempting continuation.} 7. exd5 Qe7+ {Giving a check with a queen with a bishop still on f8 looks like a fatal mistake. However, it's good to understand Black's reasonging. The queen is likely to go to b4 . White's response is both spectacular and strong.} 8. Kd2 {Extra points for style! The alternatives were clearly worse.} Qb4+ 9. Kc1 Ne7 10. Bxc7 {If White gets to d6 with a pawn, the game is practically decided as it would paralyze Black's development.} Nxd5 11. a3 Qa4 12. Bg3 d6 13. Nxd4 {Threatening Bb5 with a fork and maintaining unbearable pressure.} *

