1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxd5 {Definitely not a sound idea for Black. Provoking White to recapture with the pawn and gain a valuable tempo on the knight will likely backfire.} 6. exd5 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Qe7+ 8. Qe2 Bxd2+ 9. Kxd2 {Let's face it. I made this course for the fancy king moves. The rest is just a bonus. Jokes aside, the endgame is around the corner, so it makes perfect sense to centralize his majesty and vacate e1 for one of the rooks. We have seen similar positions in the previous chapter.} Qxe2+ 10. Bxe2 {White enjoys space advantage, and the d -pawn will soon be recaptured. On top of that, there is a significant development lead and the possibility of putting the rooks on central files. Undoubtedly, it's much easier to play this position with White.} Nb4 11. Rhe1 ({Another game saw} 11. Bc4 {( d6⩲ As usual, this pawn sacrifice deserves considerations.)} O-O 12. Nxd4 c6 13. d6 {With full positional domination in 1-0 Kostic, V (2455)-Schoellmann, J (2245) Bayern 2002.}) 11... O-O 12. d6 cxd6 13. Nxd4 {Intending Bf3 followed by Rad1 paralyzing Black's queenside.} *


