1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bb4+ 8. Kf1 {Unfortunately, the right to castle is permanently lost. Well, at least until the next game. On a positive note, White will win the d pawn back. Typically, the rook from a1 will be moved to e1 .} O-O {Assuming that White doesn't even want to take the pawn in many instances, what's the point of protecting it? It is quite logical. I have to admit.} 9. Qxd4 h6 {For aesthetic reasons, let's make this our mainline.} 10. Bd3 {Improving the bishop while attacking another one.} Qe7 {We reached a position, where White starts a shocking attack.} 11. Bxh6 {Unexpectedly, White can afford to sacrifice the bishop, as he will swiftly open the g file with an astonishing attack.} gxh6 12. g4 {Intending g4 - g5 and Rg1 - probably in that order.} Bc5 13. Qf4 Nxd5 14. Qxh6 f6 15. Re1 Qg7 16. Qh5 {At first glance, it seems that White is retreating with the queen and thus the attack will slow down. Quite the opposite!   Her majesty attacks Black’s minor pieces along the 5th rank, which maintains the initiative. On top of that, the majestic bishop on d3 may be transferred to c4 , creating new threats along the a2 - g8 diagonal.   White’s domination of the light squares is indisputable. Hence, transferring our pony to h4 and ultimately to f5 or g6 looks like a decent idea, as well.} c6 17. Nh4 d6 18. Ng6 {White's attack looks really scary, c2 - c4 might be a useful resource facilitating the fight over e7 .} *

