1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 d6 {An extremely rare continuation (not only at the high level). Such a move is most likely to be played by someone surprised by the Belgrade Gambit and trying to avoid your opening preparation.   Nice try! Luckily, we anticipated that as well.} 6. Nxd4 ({Simple and efficient. Obviously, centralization of the next minor piece is very beneficial, but it is also important to keep in mind that the e4 pawn might be hanging in some lines. As a matter of fact, White already indirectly protects the e4 pawn, as taking it would lead to a completely lost position for Black. Now we will cover as many as five options for Black: A1: Nxe4 , A2: Nxd5 , A3: Bd7 , A4: Bg4 , A5:} 6. Nxd4 {and A6:} Be7 {.}) 6... Nxe4 {Gluttony in the opening is particularly unhealthy! By ignoring the opening principles, Black gets into tactical problems.} 7. Nb5 {In the next move, White will capture the c7 pawn and be a step away from winning.} Rb8 {This just makes things even worse.} 8. Nbxc7+ Kd7 9. Qg4+ f5 10. Qxf5# {As demonstrated, trying to protect the rook loses on spot.} *

