1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 d6 {An extremely rare continuation (not only at the high level). Such a move is most likely to be played by someone surprised by the Belgrade Gambit and trying to avoid your opening preparation.   Nice try! Luckily, we anticipated that as well.} 6. Nxd4 ({Simple and efficient. Obviously, centralization of the next minor piece is very beneficial, but it is also important to keep in mind that the e4 pawn might be hanging in some lines. As a matter of fact, White already indirectly protects the e4 pawn, as taking it would lead to a completely lost position for Black. Now we will cover as many as five options for Black: A1: Nxe4 , A2: Nxd5 , A3: Bd7 , A4: Bg4 , A5:} 6. Nxd4 {and A6:} Be7 {.}) 6... Nxd5 {Exchanging minor pieces is Black's typical defensive resource. From a strategic point of view, this makes perfect sense. Black has less space, so trading is beneficial.} 7. exd5 Ne5 {Black tries to preserve an active knight in the centre. It seems slightly more natural than the exchange of the ponies.} 8. f4 Ng4 {This leads to tactical trouble.} 9. Bb5+ {Oops! Black is virtually forced to move the king as the other moves lose material.} Ke7 {I mean, if you manage to force Black to play like that, I will consider this my personal success.} 10. h3 Nh6 11. Qe2+ Kf6 {Black has nothing better to play and his only hope is to play g7 - g6 followed by Kg7 praying to find safety on kingside.} 12. Be3 {Black's position is simply ridiculous. Checkmate is on the horizon. Ideally, we would like to put the bishop on d4 .} *

