1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 d6 {An extremely rare continuation (not only at the high level). Such a move is most likely to be played by someone surprised by the Belgrade Gambit and trying to avoid your opening preparation.   Nice try! Luckily, we anticipated that as well.} 6. Nxd4 ({Simple and efficient. Obviously, centralization of the next minor piece is very beneficial, but it is also important to keep in mind that the e4 pawn might be hanging in some lines. As a matter of fact, White already indirectly protects the e4 pawn, as taking it would lead to a completely lost position for Black. Now we will cover as many as five options for Black: A1: Nxe4 , A2: Nxd5 , A3: Bd7 , A4: Bg4 , A5:} 6. Nxd4 {and A6:} Be7 {.}) 6... Nxd5 {Exchanging minor pieces is Black's typical defensive resource. From a strategic point of view, this makes perfect sense. Black has less space, so trading is beneficial.} 7. exd5 Ne5 {Black tries to preserve an active knight in the centre. It seems slightly more natural than the exchange of the ponies.} 8. f4 Ng6 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Bxd7+ {Precision is required. White needs to play quite aggresively to maintain the advantage. We will get the dividends later.} (10. Qe2+ $6 {this just helps Black to develop pieces} Be7 {a huge portion of White's advantage evaporated as Black is about to castle.}) 10... Qxd7 11. f5 Ne5 12. f6 {White attemps to spoil Black's pawn structure and secure the maginificent f5 outpost for the knight.} gxf6 13. O-O {The f6 pawn is horribly weak and the f5 square is waiting to be occuppied by the knight. When that happens, the black bishop will have difficult life and hence, Black will face a challenging task to finish development. Despite the pawn deficit, White dominates strategically.} *


