1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 d6 {An extremely rare continuation (not only at the high level). Such a move is most likely to be played by someone surprised by the Belgrade Gambit and trying to avoid your opening preparation.   Nice try! Luckily, we anticipated that as well.} 6. Nxd4 ({Simple and efficient. Obviously, centralization of the next minor piece is very beneficial, but it is also important to keep in mind that the e4 pawn might be hanging in some lines. As a matter of fact, White already indirectly protects the e4 pawn, as taking it would lead to a completely lost position for Black. Now we will cover as many as five options for Black: A1: Nxe4 , A2: Nxd5 , A3: Bd7 , A4: Bg4 , A5:} 6. Nxd4 {and A6:} Be7 {.}) 6... Nxd5 {Exchanging minor pieces is Black's typical defensive resource. From a strategic point of view, this makes perfect sense. Black has less space, so trading is beneficial.} 7. exd5 Ne5 {Black tries to preserve an active knight in the centre. It seems slightly more natural than the exchange of the ponies.} 8. f4 Ng6 9. Qd3 {This leads to a completely different setup, but a very promising one! Centralization of the queen may give White further interesting possibilities as later on the queen could be used along the 3rd rank or be used to control f5 square, or even jump on b5 with a check in some lines.} Be7 10. Bd2 O-O 11. O-O-O {This time we castle queenside.} Bf6 12. g3 {I like the way White dominates the Black pieces. The space advantage and better central control give White a pleasant edge. The main idea is to push the kingside pawns in order to open the position there and get access to the Black king.} *

