1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 d6 {An extremely rare continuation (not only at the high level). Such a move is most likely to be played by someone surprised by the Belgrade Gambit and trying to avoid your opening preparation.   Nice try! Luckily, we anticipated that as well.} 6. Nxd4 ({Simple and efficient. Obviously, centralization of the next minor piece is very beneficial, but it is also important to keep in mind that the e4 pawn might be hanging in some lines. As a matter of fact, White already indirectly protects the e4 pawn, as taking it would lead to a completely lost position for Black. Now we will cover as many as five options for Black: A1: Nxe4 , A2: Nxd5 , A3: Bd7 , A4: Bg4 , A5:} 6. Nxd4 {and A6:} Be7 {.}) 6... Bd7 {This is certainly not the most ambitious move but it is in a way consistent with Black's strategy so far - solid play without taking unnecessary risks. Now we have 2 interesting alternatives: 7.c4 supporting the pride and joy of our position (my preferred choice), i.e. the knight on d5 or 7.Bc4 with swift development and activity.} 7. c4 {This is a reasonable continuation in case you feel like the more straightforward 7.Bc4 does not seem to promise enough advantage. The main purpose of this move is to change the character of the position and take the most of our central control. One of Black's main strategic remedies against the Belgrade Gambit is an exchange of the knights on d5 , which is often followed by massive simplifications. By playing c4 , we will get the additional possibility of recapturing on d5 with the c pawn. Hence, the pawn structure will not be symmetric and the arising imbalances should favour White.} Nxd5 {This time the simplifications will not be enough for equality.} 8. cxd5 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 {Now we see the benefit of c2 - c4 move. The pawn structure is no longer symmetric and the potential pressure along c file already looks promising. However, the most important factor is Black's problematic development. Your next task is development of both bishops - perhaps to d3 and d2 or f4 , castle and bring a rook or two to c file. Advancing the f pawn in order to prepare e4 - e5 later on might also be a sound idea.} *

