1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 d6 {An extremely rare continuation (not only at the high level). Such a move is most likely to be played by someone surprised by the Belgrade Gambit and trying to avoid your opening preparation.   Nice try! Luckily, we anticipated that as well.} 6. Nxd4 ({Simple and efficient. Obviously, centralization of the next minor piece is very beneficial, but it is also important to keep in mind that the e4 pawn might be hanging in some lines. As a matter of fact, White already indirectly protects the e4 pawn, as taking it would lead to a completely lost position for Black. Now we will cover as many as five options for Black: A1: Nxe4 , A2: Nxd5 , A3: Bd7 , A4: Bg4 , A5:} 6. Nxd4 {and A6:} Be7 {.}) 6... Bd7 {This is certainly not the most ambitious move but it is in a way consistent with Black's strategy so far - solid play without taking unnecessary risks. Now we have 2 interesting alternatives: 7.c4 supporting the pride and joy of our position (my preferred choice), i.e. the knight on d5 or 7.Bc4 with swift development and activity.} 7. c4 {This is a reasonable continuation in case you feel like the more straightforward 7.Bc4 does not seem to promise enough advantage. The main purpose of this move is to change the character of the position and take the most of our central control. One of Black's main strategic remedies against the Belgrade Gambit is an exchange of the knights on d5 , which is often followed by massive simplifications. By playing c4 , we will get the additional possibility of recapturing on d5 with the c pawn. Hence, the pawn structure will not be symmetric and the arising imbalances should favour White.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 {Clearly, White can already call this opening a grand success. Complete grip in the centre and activity should be enough to secure a good game.} Be7 9. Nxe7 {Definitely not an obvious decision but the engine's top choice. Apparently, it's important to trade this bishop before Black captures on d5 and puts it on f6 . The following moves are far from being forcing. Yet, I find the engine's suggested continuation instructive.} Qxe7 10. f3 {White's pawn structure resembles the one from Maroczy Bind. In that line, Black has a powerful bishop on g7 . In the present position, White has more space accompanied by a bishop pair.} Bc6 11. Be2 a5 12. Be3 O-O 13. O-O {This seems much more rational than castling long.} Nd7 {Black tries to find a better spot for the knight and potentially breaks the centre with f7 - f5 .} 14. Rae1 {Anticipating any action along the e file.} Rfe8 15. Bd1 {Now Stockfish shows how the bishops are supposed to be coordinated.} a4 16. Qc3 Nc5 17. Bc2 Qe5 18. Bd4 {White is in command of the centre. Let's not forget that we have the powerful queen-bishop battery. On top of that, he enjoys the bishop pair in a (potentially) open position. White should try pushing the pawn majority on kingside and thus opening the position. In turn, Black will be interested in improving his position to the maximum, i. e. by playing Qg5 , f6 and potentially adding some pressure on the e4 pawn so that White is unable to move it. In such an instance, you may always try to open the second front on queenside, e.g., by playing b2 - b4 . In long rung, White has more active options.} *

