1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 d6 {An extremely rare continuation (not only at the high level). Such a move is most likely to be played by someone surprised by the Belgrade Gambit and trying to avoid your opening preparation.   Nice try! Luckily, we anticipated that as well.} 6. Nxd4 ({Simple and efficient. Obviously, centralization of the next minor piece is very beneficial, but it is also important to keep in mind that the e4 pawn might be hanging in some lines. As a matter of fact, White already indirectly protects the e4 pawn, as taking it would lead to a completely lost position for Black. Now we will cover as many as five options for Black: A1: Nxe4 , A2: Nxd5 , A3: Bd7 , A4: Bg4 , A5:} 6. Nxd4 {and A6:} Be7 {.}) 6... Bd7 {This is certainly not the most ambitious move but it is in a way consistent with Black's strategy so far - solid play without taking unnecessary risks. Now we have 2 interesting alternatives: 7.c4 supporting the pride and joy of our position (my preferred choice), i.e. the knight on d5 or 7.Bc4 with swift development and activity.} 7. c4 {This is a reasonable continuation in case you feel like the more straightforward 7.Bc4 does not seem to promise enough advantage. The main purpose of this move is to change the character of the position and take the most of our central control. One of Black's main strategic remedies against the Belgrade Gambit is an exchange of the knights on d5 , which is often followed by massive simplifications. By playing c4 , we will get the additional possibility of recapturing on d5 with the c pawn. Hence, the pawn structure will not be symmetric and the arising imbalances should favour White.} Be7 {On one hand, White is significantly more active. On the other one, Black enjoys a lead in development and a very solid position. Let's keep in mind that the pawn on e4 requires protection as well. There's a tough choice to be made: retreat this beatiful knight to c3 and lose time or exchange the other one.} 8. Nxc6 (8. Nc3 $5 {This might be an interesting attempt in case you wish to keep the game as complex as possible. White's central control should secure good long-term chances. The next step will be to develop both bishops (to e2 and e3 ) and then castle. An interesting concept might be a retreat of the knight to c2 . The more pieces we manage to keep on the board, the more Black will suffer from the lack of space.}) 8... Bxc6 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O {White enjoys a solid plus, mainly due to space advantage, activity and a phenomenal knight on d5 . Make sure to develop the other bishop (probably to e3 ) next. After that, things get blurred and depend on Black's reaction. In order to safeguard the bishop on e3 and protect e4 , you may consider f2 - f3 and Qd2 . Centralization of rooks should follow. If Black takes on d5 , you should probably take back with the c pawn.} *


