1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 d6 {An extremely rare continuation (not only at the high level). Such a move is most likely to be played by someone surprised by the Belgrade Gambit and trying to avoid your opening preparation.   Nice try! Luckily, we anticipated that as well.} 6. Nxd4 ({Simple and efficient. Obviously, centralization of the next minor piece is very beneficial, but it is also important to keep in mind that the e4 pawn might be hanging in some lines. As a matter of fact, White already indirectly protects the e4 pawn, as taking it would lead to a completely lost position for Black. Now we will cover as many as five options for Black: A1: Nxe4 , A2: Nxd5 , A3: Bd7 , A4: Bg4 , A5:} 6. Nxd4 {and A6:} Be7 {.}) 6... Bd7 {This is certainly not the most ambitious move but it is in a way consistent with Black's strategy so far - solid play without taking unnecessary risks. Now we have 2 interesting alternatives: 7.c4 supporting the pride and joy of our position (my preferred choice), i.e. the knight on d5 or 7.Bc4 with swift development and activity.} 7. Bc4 {Quick development in the spirit of the Belgrade Gambit. Once more, Black is tempted to take on e4 .} Be7 8. Nxe7 {The bishop pair in an open position has to be worth something, right?} Qxe7 9. O-O O-O 10. f3 {Safeguarding the e4 pawn and preparing a possible regrouping.} Ne5 11. Be2 {The bishop will be safer here than on b3 . Keep in mind that Black may try c7 - c5 and even c5 - c4 later. With the bishop on b3 you would already be looking for ways to avoid losing it.} c5 12. Nb3 Be6 13. Bf4 {Currently, White is threatening Nxc5 with a clear advantage (the d6 pawn might be overloaded). Overall, the position is approximately balanced but if this is true, then due to the bishop pair, White should enjoy the better side of equality in long run. The next step is to connect the rooks, possibly by Qd2 and try to prevent Black's d6 - d5 (or at lest make it less efficient).} *

