1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 d6 {An extremely rare continuation (not only at the high level). Such a move is most likely to be played by someone surprised by the Belgrade Gambit and trying to avoid your opening preparation.   Nice try! Luckily, we anticipated that as well.} 6. Nxd4 ({Simple and efficient. Obviously, centralization of the next minor piece is very beneficial, but it is also important to keep in mind that the e4 pawn might be hanging in some lines. As a matter of fact, White already indirectly protects the e4 pawn, as taking it would lead to a completely lost position for Black. Now we will cover as many as five options for Black: A1: Nxe4 , A2: Nxd5 , A3: Bd7 , A4: Bg4 , A5:} 6. Nxd4 {and A6:} Be7 {.}) 6... Nxd4 {Conceptually, it makes perfect sense for Black to eliminate the knights in order to play a dull position. Chess without those unpredictable pieces is just meaningless if you ask me. Everything becomes so simple and unidimensional. Luckily for us, Black chose the wrong moment for such a trade! Capturing on d4 may only be efficient if Black is ready to exchange the other pair of knights without haltering his development. In other words, the bishop needs to be on e7 already. We'll see why in a moment.} 7. Qxd4 {The activity of the White queen immediately becomes evident. The key to understanding this position is that Black is unable to play 7... Nxd5 8.exd5 (always with the pawn) and then 8... Be7 as the g7 pawn is under attack by the queen. Hence, Black's development becomes difficult to say the least.} Nxd5 8. exd5 {Black is temporarily unable to develop the bishop from f8 as then the g7 pawn would fall. White's play is relatively simple: develop the bishops and castle (probably short) as quickly as you can to potentially disturb the Black king along the e file by placing a rook there. I'm really not sure how he is supposed to proceed but let's see a sample line so that you feel more comfortable in the approaching battle (more like slaughter!).} Bf5 (8... Be7 9. Qxg7 {I hope a healthy pawn advantage after just nine moves will be satisfactory.}) 9. Bb5+ Bd7 {This is practically forced as the king has to be defended.} 10. O-O {Wait, are we blundering a piece? There's a bishop on b5 hanging. What are you doing?!} Bxb5 11. Re1+ {I just thought you'd be interested in winning faster. I'm sorry if I misinterpreteted your intentions when you bought this course.} Be7 12. Qxg7 {Jokes aside, White's attack is overwhelming thanks to the pin along the e-file. White is about to play Bg5 putting even more pressure on this poor bishop on e7 . I ALMOST feel sorry for Black.} ({Rf8} 12. Bg5 f6 13. Bxf6 {Rxf6 Qxf6+- White has a material advantage and a simple crushing idea: Re3 , Rae1 to follow in order to win the bishop on e7 and possibly give checkmate. The engine says I should already move on to another line, as analyzing this further is pointless. White should win soon.}) ({Kd7} 12. Qg4 {An important move, which forces the king to go back to e-file. Ke8 Bh6 White prepares a cunning tactical idea: Qg7 and then if Rf8 , we simply take the rook with a queen as it's protected by the bishop, and Black's bishop is pinned. Of course, the main threat remains the same: doubling up along the e-file with the rook to win the e7 bishop. Black is defenceless against this idea.} Qd7 $4 {Loses by force and depicts my idea.} 13. Qxg7 Rf8 14. Qxf8+) *

