1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 d6 {An extremely rare continuation (not only at the high level). Such a move is most likely to be played by someone surprised by the Belgrade Gambit and trying to avoid your opening preparation.   Nice try! Luckily, we anticipated that as well.} 6. Nxd4 ({Simple and efficient. Obviously, centralization of the next minor piece is very beneficial, but it is also important to keep in mind that the e4 pawn might be hanging in some lines. As a matter of fact, White already indirectly protects the e4 pawn, as taking it would lead to a completely lost position for Black. Now we will cover as many as five options for Black: A1: Nxe4 , A2: Nxd5 , A3: Bd7 , A4: Bg4 , A5:} 6. Nxd4 {and A6:} Be7 {.}) 6... Nxd4 {Conceptually, it makes perfect sense for Black to eliminate the knights in order to play a dull position. Chess without those unpredictable pieces is just meaningless if you ask me. Everything becomes so simple and unidimensional. Luckily for us, Black chose the wrong moment for such a trade! Capturing on d4 may only be efficient if Black is ready to exchange the other pair of knights without haltering his development. In other words, the bishop needs to be on e7 already. We'll see why in a moment.} 7. Qxd4 {The activity of the White queen immediately becomes evident. The key to understanding this position is that Black is unable to play 7... Nxd5 8.exd5 (always with the pawn) and then 8... Be7 as the g7 pawn is under attack by the queen. Hence, Black's development becomes difficult to say the least.} Be7 {This is the only reasonable continuation for Black, intending to take on d5 , then castle, and play Bf6 with good play. White needs to react.} 8. Nxe7 {This is the only way to throw a spanner in Black's works. I always have tears in my eyes when having to get rid of the d5 knight but at the very least we get the bishop pair. Combined with activity and slight space advantage, this should be enough to secure a solid edge.} Qxe7 9. Bd3 {Black has numerous options here so I took the liberty of analyzing only the most critical lines. I believe you should be able to handle the rest with logical moves.} Qe5 {Black attempts to clarify the situation by exchanging the queens. It's not such a bad idea. The character of the game obviously changed as we are facing more strategic dilemmas now.} 10. Qxe5+ {I chose to exchange the queens on Black's terms as the alternatives looked less promissing. White's main trump is the bishop pair, so you can probably imagine that White will benefit from playing an open position or a position, when the action takes place on both parts of the board simultaneously. Squeezing this will not be easy. However, I strongly believe that White doesn't risk anything here.} dxe5 11. a4 {I really like this concept as it opens new possibilities. White's main idea is simply to push the a and b pawns to soften Black's pawn structure on queenside. Perhaps the ideal sequence of moves is a4 - a5 and only then b2 - b4 . Otherwise, Black could counter b2 - b4 with a7 - a5 himself. It's tricky, I know. But that's why I'm here for you. If Black meets a4 with a5 , it will mean leaving some queenside pawns on dark squares, which is exactly what we are hoping for with the dark-squared bishop. Another idea in some positions could be: Ra3 - Rb3 / Rc3 to attack Black's pawns. Let's take a look at the engine's top choice for both sides.} Be6 12. a5 O-O-O 13. O-O a6 14. b4 {It's the kind of position where White generally plays for 2 results: winning or drawing. It's difficult to imagine a realistic counterplay for Black. White may try to open the queenside with pawn advance or restrict himself to positional means, such as Bb2 followed by centralization of the rooks.} *


