1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 d6 {An extremely rare continuation (not only at the high level). Such a move is most likely to be played by someone surprised by the Belgrade Gambit and trying to avoid your opening preparation.   Nice try! Luckily, we anticipated that as well.} 6. Nxd4 ({Simple and efficient. Obviously, centralization of the next minor piece is very beneficial, but it is also important to keep in mind that the e4 pawn might be hanging in some lines. As a matter of fact, White already indirectly protects the e4 pawn, as taking it would lead to a completely lost position for Black. Now we will cover as many as five options for Black: A1: Nxe4 , A2: Nxd5 , A3: Bd7 , A4: Bg4 , A5:} 6. Nxd4 {and A6:} Be7 {.}) 6... Nxd4 {Conceptually, it makes perfect sense for Black to eliminate the knights in order to play a dull position. Chess without those unpredictable pieces is just meaningless if you ask me. Everything becomes so simple and unidimensional. Luckily for us, Black chose the wrong moment for such a trade! Capturing on d4 may only be efficient if Black is ready to exchange the other pair of knights without haltering his development. In other words, the bishop needs to be on e7 already. We'll see why in a moment.} 7. Qxd4 {The activity of the White queen immediately becomes evident. The key to understanding this position is that Black is unable to play 7... Nxd5 8.exd5 (always with the pawn) and then 8... Be7 as the g7 pawn is under attack by the queen. Hence, Black's development becomes difficult to say the least.} Be7 {This is the only reasonable continuation for Black, intending to take on d5 , then castle, and play Bf6 with good play. White needs to react.} 8. Nxe7 {This is the only way to throw a spanner in Black's works. I always have tears in my eyes when having to get rid of the d5 knight but at the very least we get the bishop pair. Combined with activity and slight space advantage, this should be enough to secure a solid edge.} Qxe7 9. Bd3 {Black has numerous options here so I took the liberty of analyzing only the most critical lines. I believe you should be able to handle the rest with logical moves.} O-O {It's just a timid move I had to include in the course as the editorial team forced me to do so. Just kidding, you're great guys! Black accepts his fate of playing a slightly worse position. Let's see a possible continuation.} 10. Bg5 h6 {Depending on your style, you may chose to play a marginally better endgame or a more complex middlegame with the bishop pair. I'd keep the bishops on the board.} 11. Bh4 {I assume that keeping things more complex will appeal more to the majority of you. After all, who plays the Belgrade Gambit in order to go straight to the endgame?} Re8 12. O-O-O {Being allowed to castle queenside is a rare occassion in our repertoire. It typically means that things went better than expected as we get to centralize a rook for free.} Qe5 13. Qxe5 Rxe5 14. f4 {It doesn't make sense to take on f6 as we decided to keep the bishop pair earlier on.} Ra5 15. a3 Bg4 16. Rd2 {It seems that White's piece coordination is just much better. We still have our precious bishops and the possibility of pushing the kingside pawns with h3 - g4 also looks appealing. As a matter of fact, Black needs to be careful in order not to drop the bishop after something like f4 - f5 followed by h2 - h3 and then g2 - g4 , when the bishop is trapped.} *

