1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 d6 {An extremely rare continuation (not only at the high level). Such a move is most likely to be played by someone surprised by the Belgrade Gambit and trying to avoid your opening preparation.   Nice try! Luckily, we anticipated that as well.} 6. Nxd4 ({Simple and efficient. Obviously, centralization of the next minor piece is very beneficial, but it is also important to keep in mind that the e4 pawn might be hanging in some lines. As a matter of fact, White already indirectly protects the e4 pawn, as taking it would lead to a completely lost position for Black. Now we will cover as many as five options for Black: A1: Nxe4 , A2: Nxd5 , A3: Bd7 , A4: Bg4 , A5:} 6. Nxd4 {and A6:} Be7 {.}) 6... Nxd4 {Conceptually, it makes perfect sense for Black to eliminate the knights in order to play a dull position. Chess without those unpredictable pieces is just meaningless if you ask me. Everything becomes so simple and unidimensional. Luckily for us, Black chose the wrong moment for such a trade! Capturing on d4 may only be efficient if Black is ready to exchange the other pair of knights without haltering his development. In other words, the bishop needs to be on e7 already. We'll see why in a moment.} 7. Qxd4 {The activity of the White queen immediately becomes evident. The key to understanding this position is that Black is unable to play 7... Nxd5 8.exd5 (always with the pawn) and then 8... Be7 as the g7 pawn is under attack by the queen. Hence, Black's development becomes difficult to say the least.} Be7 {This is the only reasonable continuation for Black, intending to take on d5 , then castle, and play Bf6 with good play. White needs to react.} 8. Nxe7 {This is the only way to throw a spanner in Black's works. I always have tears in my eyes when having to get rid of the d5 knight but at the very least we get the bishop pair. Combined with activity and slight space advantage, this should be enough to secure a solid edge.} Qxe7 9. Bd3 {Black has numerous options here so I took the liberty of analyzing only the most critical lines. I believe you should be able to handle the rest with logical moves.} O-O {It's just a timid move I had to include in the course as the editorial team forced me to do so. Just kidding, you're great guys! Black accepts his fate of playing a slightly worse position. Let's see a possible continuation.} 10. Bg5 h6 {Depending on your style, you may chose to play a marginally better endgame or a more complex middlegame with the bishop pair. I'd keep the bishops on the board.} 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Qxf6 gxf6 13. Kd2 {Remember that in the endgame the king is supposed to be used actively. There is no point in castling as we can immediately centralize it and connect the rook, while keeping the king safe behind the bishop.} Re8 14. a4 a5 15. Ra3 {This is the engine's favourite idea. Who am I to question it? White will attack the b and c pawns next. The other rook will probably just go to e1 and then possiblt to f3 or g3 via e3 .} Bd7 16. Rc3 {We should be fine with exchanging the a pawn for the c pawn should Black decide to play Bxa4 . Black's b & d pawns would be vulnerable then.} Bxa4 17. Rxc7 Bc6 18. Re1 {White's better pawn structure  (less pawn islands) and activity secures a promissing advantage.} *

