 Qxe7 9. Bd3 {Black has numerous options here so I took the liberty of analyzing only the most critical lines. I believe you should be able to handle the rest with logical moves.} O-O {It's just a timid move I had to include in the course as the editorial team forced me to do so. Just kidding, you're great guys! Black accepts his fate of playing a slightly worse position. Let's see a possible continuation.} 10. Bg5 h6 {Depending on your style, you may chose to play a marginally better endgame or a more complex middlegame with the bishop pair. I'd keep the bishops on the board.} 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Qxf6 gxf6 13. Kd2 {Remember that in the endgame the king is supposed to be used actively. There is no point in castling as we can immediately centralize it and connect the rook, while keeping the king safe behind the bishop.} Re8 14. a4 a5 15. Ra3 {This is the engine's favourite idea. Who am I to question it? White will attack the b and c pawns next. The other rook will probably just go to e1 and then possiblt to f3 or g3 via e3 .} Bd7 16. Rc3 {We should be fine with exchanging the a pawn for the c pawn should Black decide to play Bxa4 . Black's b & d pawns would be vulnerable then.} Rac8 17. f3 Re5 18. b3 Kf8 19. g4 {Let's stop here. White has a much better pawn structure - it's only drawback is that the majority of the pawns is placed on light squares. However, Black is unable to undouble his f pawns now, which means he is restricted to passive defense. Things are not forced but White's position is risk-free. You still need to improve the rook from h1 - possibly by putting it on e1 and that's a good starting point. Another idea could be Bc4 followed by Rd3 , c2 - c3 intending to make progress on queenside with b3 - b4 at some point later in the game.} *

