1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 d6 {An extremely rare continuation (not only at the high level). Such a move is most likely to be played by someone surprised by the Belgrade Gambit and trying to avoid your opening preparation.   Nice try! Luckily, we anticipated that as well.} 6. Nxd4 ({Simple and efficient. Obviously, centralization of the next minor piece is very beneficial, but it is also important to keep in mind that the e4 pawn might be hanging in some lines. As a matter of fact, White already indirectly protects the e4 pawn, as taking it would lead to a completely lost position for Black. Now we will cover as many as five options for Black: A1: Nxe4 , A2: Nxd5 , A3: Bd7 , A4: Bg4 , A5:} 6. Nxd4 {and A6:} Be7 {.}) 6... Be7 7. Bb5 Bd7 {Surprisingly, this is a very important position. So far, White has obtained a promising edge, but it's somewhat elusive. It's critical to understand that Black threatens massive exchanges of minor pieces and when that happens, Black's problems will be over.} 8. Nf5 {This is an attempt to make things spicy and imbalanced. Black has a chance to take the knight and worsen White's pawn structure. In return, White gets the bishop pair and a strange type of a pawn majority on kingside.} (8. O-O $6 {positionally, this is dubious as it allows massive simplifications.} Nxd5 9. exd5 Nxd4 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Qxd4 O-O {Black is certainly not worse. It's a type of position we want to avoid at any cost. Simple, dull, yuck!}) 8... Bxf5 {It's a bold decision, but the knight was really annoying on f5 .} 9. exf5 O-O 10. O-O {White enjoys a slightly more pleasant position, but it's not much. The game is still complex, though, and I prefer White due to the bishop pair in an open position and the possibility of launching a pawn attack on the kingside. This position was seen in Almasi-Eismont, 1993.} Nxd5 11. Qxd5 {Much better was: Certainly possible but rather passive.} Qd7 12. c3 {Covering d4 square as well as reducing Black's potential activity along a1 - h8 diagonal. Later, White may also attempt to reposition the bishop to c2 and use it to attack along the b1 - h7 diagonal, possibly with the queen on d3 .} a6 13. Ba4 b5 {If White was forced to go back to b3 and Black had a chance to attack said bishop by Na5 , Black would have a satisfactory position. At this point, White maintains the bishop pair, which also secures pretty sweet attacking chances on Black's king.} 14. Bc2 Ne5 15. Qe4 {f5 - f6 is in the air} Bf6 16. g4 {White's attack turns out to be quite dangerous as Black has limited time to consolidate.} Qc6 17. Qxc6 Nxc6 18. g5 Be7 19. Be4 {The pin along the long diagonal leads to material gains for White.} *

