1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 d6 {An extremely rare continuation (not only at the high level). Such a move is most likely to be played by someone surprised by the Belgrade Gambit and trying to avoid your opening preparation.   Nice try! Luckily, we anticipated that as well.} 6. Nxd4 ({Simple and efficient. Obviously, centralization of the next minor piece is very beneficial, but it is also important to keep in mind that the e4 pawn might be hanging in some lines. As a matter of fact, White already indirectly protects the e4 pawn, as taking it would lead to a completely lost position for Black. Now we will cover as many as five options for Black: A1: Nxe4 , A2: Nxd5 , A3: Bd7 , A4: Bg4 , A5:} 6. Nxd4 {and A6:} Be7 {.}) 6... Be7 7. Bb5 Bd7 {Surprisingly, this is a very important position. So far, White has obtained a promising edge, but it's somewhat elusive. It's critical to understand that Black threatens massive exchanges of minor pieces and when that happens, Black's problems will be over.} 8. Nf5 {This is an attempt to make things spicy and imbalanced. Black has a chance to take the knight and worsen White's pawn structure. In return, White gets the bishop pair and a strange type of a pawn majority on kingside.} (8. O-O $6 {positionally, this is dubious as it allows massive simplifications.} Nxd5 9. exd5 Nxd4 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Qxd4 O-O {Black is certainly not worse. It's a type of position we want to avoid at any cost. Simple, dull, yuck!}) 8... Bxf5 {It's a bold decision, but the knight was really annoying on f5 .} 9. exf5 O-O 10. O-O {White enjoys a slightly more pleasant position, but it's not much. The game is still complex, though, and I prefer White due to the bishop pair in an open position and the possibility of launching a pawn attack on the kingside. This position was seen in Almasi-Eismont, 1993.} Nxd5 11. Qxd5 {Much better was: Certainly possible but rather passive.} Qd7 12. c3 {Covering d4 square as well as reducing Black's potential activity along a1 - h8 diagonal. Later, White may also attempt to reposition the bishop to c2 and use it to attack along the b1 - h7 diagonal, possibly with the queen on d3 .} a6 13. Ba4 Bf6 {White is obliged to attack or else he will lose the momentum.} 14. g4 {The pawn avalanche should not be underestimated. White threatens to play g4 - g5 .} (14. Bd2 $6 {I don't see how the bishop is better on d2 as compared to c1 .} b5 15. Bc2 Ne5 16. Rae1 Rfe8 17. Bc1 c6 18. Qd1 d5 19. Re2 {White didn't achieve enough activity for the compromised pawn structure.}) 14... g6 15. Bc2 {White threatens to win a pawn (exploiting the pinned pawn on f7 ). What's more, in a moment, g5 - f6 might be a strong continuation. In case the g file opens, White can always play Kh1 and Rg1 .} *

