{With mutual chances after d5 . White should try to put the bishop on e3 or d4 , perhaps play c3 and Qd3 and consider doubling the rooks along the e file. Depending on the situation, a2 - a4 might be an idea to create some action on the queenside. Still, White is generally supposed to look into activity on kingside. Advancing f&g pawns seems a good try.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 d6 {An extremely rare continuation (not only at the high level). Such a move is most likely to be played by someone surprised by the Belgrade Gambit and trying to avoid your opening preparation.   Nice try! Luckily, we anticipated that as well.} 6. Nxd4 ({Simple and efficient. Obviously, centralization of the next minor piece is very beneficial, but it is also important to keep in mind that the e4 pawn might be hanging in some lines. As a matter of fact, White already indirectly protects the e4 pawn, as taking it would lead to a completely lost position for Black. Now we will cover as many as five options for Black: A1: Nxe4 , A2: Nxd5 , A3: Bd7 , A4: Bg4 , A5:} 6. Nxd4 {and A6:} Be7 {.}) 6... Be7 7. Bb5 Bd7 {Surprisingly, this is a very important position. So far, White has obtained a promising edge, but it's somewhat elusive. It's critical to understand that Black threatens massive exchanges of minor pieces and when that happens, Black's problems will be over.} 8. Nf5 {This is an attempt to make things spicy and imbalanced. Black has a chance to take the knight and worsen White's pawn structure. In return, White gets the bishop pair and a strange type of a pawn majority on kingside.} (8. O-O $6 {positionally, this is dubious as it allows massive simplifications.} Nxd5 9. exd5 Nxd4 10. Bxd7+ Qxd7 11. Qxd4 O-O {Black is certainly not worse. It's a type of position we want to avoid at any cost. Simple, dull, yuck!}) 8... Bxf5 {It's a bold decision, but the knight was really annoying on f5 .} 9. exf5 a6 {This is a huge improvement over the stem game.} 10. Ba4 b5 11. Bb3 O-O 12. O-O Na5 {Black tries to exchange White's light-squared bishop and follow it up with a capture on d5 and repositioning of the bishop to f6 . However, it seems that as long as White maintains the control over light squares, he should have slightly better practical chances.} 13. Re1 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 c6 15. Bf3 *

