1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 h6 {This move actually makes some sense. Black is simply trying to prevent 6.Bg5 with the irritating pin. Yet, it is a rather rare choice for Black - at least at a higher level.   The great majority of this chapter originates from computer analysis. Still, it's worth learning these lines as they nicely present certain ideas, which we will use in other positions.   I don't recommend memorizing all of it. Try to treat this chapter as a unique chance to increase your resourcefulness.   When preparing this chapter, I didn't expect to find so many fascinating tactical and strategic ideas. Welcome to the Belgrade jungle!} 6. Bf4 {White develops the bishop, attacking the c7 pawn and threatening to score the point.} Bb4+ {It's always worth checking the strength of the most forcing continuations. However, this time Black shouldn't be so aggressive. The following sequence of moves is quite forcing and requires memorization.   In case you realize in the game that your memory malfunctions, make sure to look for dynamic moves that apply pressure on Black.} 7. Nxb4 Nxb4 8. e5 {Put your hands in the air and give me all your money! The Black knights are likely to wander around pointlessly.} Nh5 9. Bd2 Nc6 10. g4 {This is why you shouldn't place the knights on the rim of the board.} d6 11. gxh5 dxe5 {White enjoys a material advantage. However, the h5 pawn is a joke (not the funny one). If we add Black's phenomenal central pawns and White's king, which got stuck in the middle of the board, to the equation, a recipe for disaster is ready. I strongly recommend approaching this position cautiously.} 12. Rg1 {I like this move as it attacks the g7 pawn and prevents Bg4 with a pin. In fact, we will be looking for a smart way to give the material back to catch up in development.} e4 13. Qe2 Qe7 14. O-O-O {Sometimes, it's worth giving back the material in order to sleep well. Development and king safety is the priority here!} exf3 15. Qxf3 Qf6 {g7 pawn was still attacked.} 16. Qe4+ Be6 17. Ba6 {It's hammer time! This incredible tactical resource creates mayhem in Black's position.} O-O-O 18. Qxc6 {What an aesthetically pleasing move.} bxa6 19. Qa8+ Kd7 20. Qxa7 Ra8 21. Qc5 {I did the most difficult part for you. White's much better due to Black's rather adventurous king and the activity of White's pieces. PRO TIP: Don't let the king escape from the centre.} *


