1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 h6 {This move actually makes some sense. Black is simply trying to prevent 6.Bg5 with the irritating pin. Yet, it is a rather rare choice for Black - at least at a higher level.   The great majority of this chapter originates from computer analysis. Still, it's worth learning these lines as they nicely present certain ideas, which we will use in other positions.   I don't recommend memorizing all of it. Try to treat this chapter as a unique chance to increase your resourcefulness.   When preparing this chapter, I didn't expect to find so many fascinating tactical and strategic ideas. Welcome to the Belgrade jungle!} 6. Bf4 {White develops the bishop, attacking the c7 pawn and threatening to score the point.} Bb4+ {It's always worth checking the strength of the most forcing continuations. However, this time Black shouldn't be so aggressive. The following sequence of moves is quite forcing and requires memorization.   In case you realize in the game that your memory malfunctions, make sure to look for dynamic moves that apply pressure on Black.} 7. Nxb4 Nxb4 8. e5 {Put your hands in the air and give me all your money! The Black knights are likely to wander around pointlessly.} Ne4 {The knights are usually well placed in the centre of the board. However, in this case, neither of the Black knights has sufficient support. Consequently, we should try to exploit their dangerous position by tactical means.} 9. a3 Nd5 {Again, a knight not protected by a pawn may be harassed easily.} 10. Qxd4 Nxf4 11. Qxe4 Ne6 12. O-O-O {White dominates due to the space advantage, better development and activity.   The engine already claims this is winning for White.   No pressure. Black's main problem is the difficulty of completing the development. b7 - b6 is impossible due to the pin along the h1 - a8 diagonal, while d7 - d6 invites White to capture on d6 , which leads to Black having a horribly weak pawn on d6 .   Castling short does not bring Black any relief as a simple Bd3 idea with Qh7 checkmate threat is in the air. In the meantime, White should choose from a variety of active moves: Bc4 / Bd3 , h4 , g4 and possibly a bit of long-term prophylaxis: Kb1 .} *

