1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 h6 {This move actually makes some sense. Black is simply trying to prevent 6.Bg5 with the irritating pin. Yet, it is a rather rare choice for Black - at least at a higher level.   The great majority of this chapter originates from computer analysis. Still, it's worth learning these lines as they nicely present certain ideas, which we will use in other positions.   I don't recommend memorizing all of it. Try to treat this chapter as a unique chance to increase your resourcefulness.   When preparing this chapter, I didn't expect to find so many fascinating tactical and strategic ideas. Welcome to the Belgrade jungle!} 6. Bf4 {White develops the bishop, attacking the c7 pawn and threatening to score the point.} Bb4+ {It's always worth checking the strength of the most forcing continuations. However, this time Black shouldn't be so aggressive. The following sequence of moves is quite forcing and requires memorization.   In case you realize in the game that your memory malfunctions, make sure to look for dynamic moves that apply pressure on Black.} 7. Nxb4 Nxb4 8. e5 {Put your hands in the air and give me all your money! The Black knights are likely to wander around pointlessly.} Ne4 {The knights are usually well placed in the centre of the board. However, in this case, neither of the Black knights has sufficient support. Consequently, we should try to exploit their dangerous position by tactical means.} 9. a3 Nc6 10. Nxd4 O-O {Castling right away looks very natural. From Black's perspective, not fighting for the centre is a drawback of this line.} 11. Nxc6 dxc6 12. Qf3 {It's certainly not the only move in this position. A lazy approach would mean exchanging the queens and playing the better endgame. Feel free to do that. My idea for this course was slightly different, though. When possible, I attempt to present the most ambitious ways to fight for the advantage. After all, this means a better chance to win by move 25.} Ng5 13. Qg3 {White may try playing h4 with an attack in a moment. This may even give you a chance to play Bxh6 !} Bf5 14. h4 Ne4 15. Qf3 {Generally, we're looking for a good moment to play Bxh6 . But please, please be careful. The bishop is still responsible for covering the d2 square. Allowing the Black queen to get there would be fatal.} Qe7 {loses material} 16. Bd3 {Black cannot protect both the knight on e4 and the bishop on f5 .} Nd6 17. O-O-O Bxd3 18. exd6 {White captures the bishop next with a winning position.} *

