1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 h6 {This move actually makes some sense. Black is simply trying to prevent 6.Bg5 with the irritating pin. Yet, it is a rather rare choice for Black - at least at a higher level.   The great majority of this chapter originates from computer analysis. Still, it's worth learning these lines as they nicely present certain ideas, which we will use in other positions.   I don't recommend memorizing all of it. Try to treat this chapter as a unique chance to increase your resourcefulness.   When preparing this chapter, I didn't expect to find so many fascinating tactical and strategic ideas. Welcome to the Belgrade jungle!} 6. Bf4 {White develops the bishop, attacking the c7 pawn and threatening to score the point.} Bb4+ {It's always worth checking the strength of the most forcing continuations. However, this time Black shouldn't be so aggressive. The following sequence of moves is quite forcing and requires memorization.   In case you realize in the game that your memory malfunctions, make sure to look for dynamic moves that apply pressure on Black.} 7. Nxb4 Nxb4 8. e5 {Put your hands in the air and give me all your money! The Black knights are likely to wander around pointlessly.} Qe7 9. Bc4 {At this point, we will investigate d5 and d6 for Black. Both seem equally logical.} d5 {a valid option} 10. Bb5+ c6 {While this move is definitely tempting; it will lead to the downfall of Black pawn formation.} 11. Be2 Nd7 12. a3 {Fasten your seatbelts as we enter a very forcing sequence of moves.} Na6 13. Bxa6 bxa6 14. Nxd4 Nxe5 {Black is up a pawn but he has two problems, which are difficult to be solved at the same time: The exposed king in the centre as well as the dubious pawn on c6 .} 15. O-O Ng6 16. Re1 Be6 17. Bg3 {This was required before capturing on c6 . White has a much healthier position with fewer pawn islands and much better piece coordination. Things are far from being forced, but the general conclusion is that Black shouldn't try to hold on to the pawn advantage given his king still being in the middle of the board.} c5 {Way too risky.} 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. Qh5 Qf7 20. Qxd5 O-O 21. Qxe6 {Objectively, this is winning due to the material advantage, which is likely to increase judging by Black's queenside pawns.} *

