1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 h6 {This move actually makes some sense. Black is simply trying to prevent 6.Bg5 with the irritating pin. Yet, it is a rather rare choice for Black - at least at a higher level.   The great majority of this chapter originates from computer analysis. Still, it's worth learning these lines as they nicely present certain ideas, which we will use in other positions.   I don't recommend memorizing all of it. Try to treat this chapter as a unique chance to increase your resourcefulness.   When preparing this chapter, I didn't expect to find so many fascinating tactical and strategic ideas. Welcome to the Belgrade jungle!} 6. Bf4 {White develops the bishop, attacking the c7 pawn and threatening to score the point.} d6 {This is the more likely move. Typically, White will just regain the pawn and try to emphasize the difference between the activity of White and Black pieces.} 7. Nxd4 Be7 {One of the most logical moves for Black. The position is not forcing but my recommendation is to simplify it a bit and convert the better development and space into structural edge.} 8. Bb5 Bd7 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Nxe7 Qxe7 11. O-O Nxe4 {This seems a bit too risky.} 12. Re1 {As usual, this pin will be lethal. Good luck defending against f2 - f3 . White has very realistic chances of winning the knight on e4 .} *

