1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 h6 {This move actually makes some sense. Black is simply trying to prevent 6.Bg5 with the irritating pin. Yet, it is a rather rare choice for Black - at least at a higher level.   The great majority of this chapter originates from computer analysis. Still, it's worth learning these lines as they nicely present certain ideas, which we will use in other positions.   I don't recommend memorizing all of it. Try to treat this chapter as a unique chance to increase your resourcefulness.   When preparing this chapter, I didn't expect to find so many fascinating tactical and strategic ideas. Welcome to the Belgrade jungle!} 6. Bf4 {White develops the bishop, attacking the c7 pawn and threatening to score the point.} Nxd5 {This move could be treated as the mainline of 5... h6 . From Black's perspective, it makes a lot of sense to take on d5 in order to develop the bishop to b4 and, later on, the queen to e7 . A very tempting continuation.} 7. exd5 Bb4+ 8. Bd2 {The only reasonable move.} Qe7+ 9. Qe2 {It's worth remembering this reaction. It seems more natural to play 9. Be2 but it's a huge positional mistake.} (9. Be2 $2 {Under no circumstances should you play this move when there's no connection between the queen and} d3 {square.} 10. cxd3 $1 {Black disrupts White's pawn formation with this little trick. The pawn on d5 will be too weak now. cxd3} Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 Nb4 {Black is about to capture the d pawn with a huge advantage.}) 9... Bxd2+ 10. Kxd2 {The key move! Since the queens will be traded anyway, it makes no sense to keep the king on e1 . The rooks need to be connected and thanks to liberating the e1 square, White may be interested in sliding the rook there to quickly attack the Black king.} Nb4 11. d6 {A temporary pawn sacrifice aimed at ruining Black's pawn structure and paralyzing the development of the bishop from c8 . It should be relatively easy to attack and win the pawn on d6 in case Black captures.} cxd6 {This is just a bonus for buying the course :)} 12. Qb5 {Black loses the knight on b4 or the queen after Re1 .} Nc6 13. Re1 Ne5 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Rxe5 {White wins the queen and likely the game.} *

