1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 h6 {This move actually makes some sense. Black is simply trying to prevent 6.Bg5 with the irritating pin. Yet, it is a rather rare choice for Black - at least at a higher level.   The great majority of this chapter originates from computer analysis. Still, it's worth learning these lines as they nicely present certain ideas, which we will use in other positions.   I don't recommend memorizing all of it. Try to treat this chapter as a unique chance to increase your resourcefulness.   When preparing this chapter, I didn't expect to find so many fascinating tactical and strategic ideas. Welcome to the Belgrade jungle!} 6. Bf4 {White develops the bishop, attacking the c7 pawn and threatening to score the point.} Nxd5 {This move could be treated as the mainline of 5... h6 . From Black's perspective, it makes a lot of sense to take on d5 in order to develop the bishop to b4 and, later on, the queen to e7 . A very tempting continuation.} 7. exd5 Qf6 8. Bd2 {It is necessary to bring the bishop back. Fortunately, Black still needs to find a good square for the knight.} Ne7 9. Bc4 Ng6 {I have to be completely honest with you. This is a good setup for Black. The knight will control the important e5 square and might even jump to f4 or h4 in certain lines. Black's dark-squared bishop will be the first activated piece, which will enable castling. Thus, I'm proposing two completely different approaches with different levels of complexity.} 10. O-O Be7 11. c3 {This is the key move in the current line. White needs to bring the dark-squared bishop back to life.} dxc3 {Black really shouldn't allow that. White has more than enough compensation for the pawn. His pieces are electrifying.} 12. Bxc3 Qf4 13. Nd4 O-O 14. g3 {Harassing the queen is a powerful strategy in this case. Not only can it be trapped in the centre, but also its vulnerability may lead to other tactical ideas, e.g. Nf5 with an attack on g7 .} Qe5 15. Nb5 Qg5 16. Nxc7 {White regaings the pawn and maintains the pressure. White's bishops are really good but possibly we should play d5 - d6 before Black plays d7 - d6 himself. Besides, White may try playing f4 - f5 and start asking uncomfortable positions to Black pieces.} *

