1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 h6 {This move actually makes some sense. Black is simply trying to prevent 6.Bg5 with the irritating pin. Yet, it is a rather rare choice for Black - at least at a higher level.   The great majority of this chapter originates from computer analysis. Still, it's worth learning these lines as they nicely present certain ideas, which we will use in other positions.   I don't recommend memorizing all of it. Try to treat this chapter as a unique chance to increase your resourcefulness.   When preparing this chapter, I didn't expect to find so many fascinating tactical and strategic ideas. Welcome to the Belgrade jungle!} 6. Bf4 {White develops the bishop, attacking the c7 pawn and threatening to score the point.} Nxd5 {This move could be treated as the mainline of 5... h6 . From Black's perspective, it makes a lot of sense to take on d5 in order to develop the bishop to b4 and, later on, the queen to e7 . A very tempting continuation.} 7. exd5 Qf6 8. Bd2 {It is necessary to bring the bishop back. Fortunately, Black still needs to find a good square for the knight.} Ne7 9. Bc4 Ng6 {I have to be completely honest with you. This is a good setup for Black. The knight will control the important e5 square and might even jump to f4 or h4 in certain lines. Black's dark-squared bishop will be the first activated piece, which will enable castling. Thus, I'm proposing two completely different approaches with different levels of complexity.} 10. Qe2+ {The check introduces the possibility of castling queenside.} Be7 11. O-O-O O-O 12. Rhe1 {White is down a pawn and the purpose is to win the d pawn back. More realistically, White should try to obtain as much compensation as possible. Black still has a few problems to be solved: completing the development without disrupting the piece coordindation.} b5 {This is engine's first choice. Black gives the pawn back in order to seize the initiative on queenside.} 13. Bxb5 Rb8 14. Bd3 Qb6 {Surprisingly, this is not precise enough. White will need to play b2 - b3 anyway so the queen could have stayed on f6 .} 15. b3 Bb7 16. Bxg6 {A very important move, which begins a forcing move sequence.} Ba3+ 17. Kb1 fxg6 18. Ne5 {Again, White threatens d7 and the Nc4 fork eliminating the pivotal bishop on a3 .} Rbd8 19. Nc4 Ba6 20. Nxb6 {The engine evaluates White's chances in the endgame slightly higher.} Bxe2 21. Rxe2 d3 22. Re4 cxb6 23. Be3 dxc2+ 24. Kxc2 {White's pawn structure is better and so is his pieces' activity. The next move will likely be Ra4 .} *

