1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 h6 {This move actually makes some sense. Black is simply trying to prevent 6.Bg5 with the irritating pin. Yet, it is a rather rare choice for Black - at least at a higher level.   The great majority of this chapter originates from computer analysis. Still, it's worth learning these lines as they nicely present certain ideas, which we will use in other positions.   I don't recommend memorizing all of it. Try to treat this chapter as a unique chance to increase your resourcefulness.   When preparing this chapter, I didn't expect to find so many fascinating tactical and strategic ideas. Welcome to the Belgrade jungle!} 6. Bf4 {White develops the bishop, attacking the c7 pawn and threatening to score the point.} Nxd5 {This move could be treated as the mainline of 5... h6 . From Black's perspective, it makes a lot of sense to take on d5 in order to develop the bishop to b4 and, later on, the queen to e7 . A very tempting continuation.} 7. exd5 Qf6 8. Bd2 {It is necessary to bring the bishop back. Fortunately, Black still needs to find a good square for the knight.} Ne7 9. Bc4 Ng6 {I have to be completely honest with you. This is a good setup for Black. The knight will control the important e5 square and might even jump to f4 or h4 in certain lines. Black's dark-squared bishop will be the first activated piece, which will enable castling. Thus, I'm proposing two completely different approaches with different levels of complexity.} 10. Qe2+ {The check introduces the possibility of castling queenside.} Be7 11. O-O-O O-O 12. Rhe1 {White is down a pawn and the purpose is to win the d pawn back. More realistically, White should try to obtain as much compensation as possible. Black still has a few problems to be solved: completing the development without disrupting the piece coordindation.} b5 {This is engine's first choice. Black gives the pawn back in order to seize the initiative on queenside.} 13. Bxb5 Rb8 14. Bd3 Ba6 {Unfortunately, sometimes the engines find great tactical ideas for the opponents.} 15. Qf1 {White sidesteps most tactical ideas, including Nf4 and d4 - d3 in some lines.} (15. Bxa6 $4 d3 {presents the tactical point. Black wins material or gives checkmate on b2 .}) 15... Qd6 {Black has another shocking idea.} 16. Bxa6 Qa3 17. Bb5 Qxa2 18. c3 {Yet another extraordinary idea for Black. It generally doesn't feel right to allow so many tactical resources on the part of the board where our king is located.} a6 19. Qc4 Qa1+ 20. Kc2 axb5 21. Rxa1 bxc4 22. Nxd4 {White may still hope to get more than half of a point as the c pawn could be attacked with Ra4 . Realistically, the position is equal.} *

