1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Bb4+ {It looks like a bad mix of ideas available to Black. White will be able to get a significant advantage in all lines.} 6. Nxb4 Nxb4 7. e5 {Let's chase those knights a bit.} Nfd5 8. Bc4 {It becomes more and more evident that something went wrong. Black has two major problems here:   1) the knights are really misplaced and separated from the rest of the position.   2) without the dark-squared bishop, Black needs to watch for moves like Bg5 , which at the very least, will compromise Black's pawn formation.   White's candidate moves are a2 - a3 and Bg5 .} d6 {Black tries to simplify the position and create the connection between the queen and the knight on d5 . Remember that centralized knights are typically as strong as bishops (even in open positions), provided that they are supported. It's just not the case here.} 9. a3 Nb6 10. Bxf7+ {A nice tactical resource, which secures White much better chances due to the exposed position of the Black king.} Kxf7 11. axb4 {White has a significant advantage due to the better king's position and a great chance of winning the d4 pawn.} *

