1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxd5 {Definitely not a sound idea for Black. Provoking White to recapture with the pawn and gain a valuable tempo on the knight will likely backfire.} 6. exd5 Nb4 {It looks like if Black used the wrong move order. Generally, Nb4 could be played, but before capturing the knight on d5 - such a continuation will be presented in a separate chapter. The Black knight will be badly positioned on b4 now. With proper play, White should be able to severely restrict its options.} 7. Bc4 c6 {Black does not have time for such moves. White quickly seizes the initiative.} 8. O-O cxd5 9. Qxd4 {A surprising, yet entirely sound piece sacrifice. Black is so behind in development that even a piece deficit will be completely irrelevant for White. The pieces already involved in the game will easily prevail.} dxc4 10. Re1+ Be7 11. Qxg7 Rf8 12. Bh6 {Black is helpless against Qxf8 threat. White wins.} *

