1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxd5 {Definitely not a sound idea for Black. Provoking White to recapture with the pawn and gain a valuable tempo on the knight will likely backfire.} 6. exd5 Nb4 {It looks like if Black used the wrong move order. Generally, Nb4 could be played, but before capturing the knight on d5 - such a continuation will be presented in a separate chapter. The Black knight will be badly positioned on b4 now. With proper play, White should be able to severely restrict its options.} 7. Bc4 Qe7+ 8. Kf1 {To an untrained eye, this may look like a strange move.   The point is to avoid any simplifications which would occur after 8.Be2.   Other moves are obviously just bad. In fact, the king is perfectly safe on f1 . What's more, sliding the king away from the e1 square vacates this important square for the rook on a1 .   It will be a recurring theme in a great many lines.   Just try picturing the rook magically jumping from a1 to e1 . Black could already resign due to the pin along the e-file. You might be wondering how the other rook should be activated. Typically, we will just play h2 - h4 and either use the rook along the h file or, in rare situations, activate it via the 3rd rank.   The truth is that putting the king on f1 is a real bargain if you consider the possibility of developing the other pieces at full speed.} b5 {We have seen this resource a few times already. Black's main idea is to develop the bishop to b7 .} 9. Bb3 {It's necessary to keep the d5 pawn on the board as it nicely limits Black's activity.} Qc5 10. Qxd4 {Simple and effective. Despite the upcoming queen trade, White will maintain a convincing edge.} Qxd4 11. Nxd4 Bb7 12. Nxb5 {White threatens to capture the c7 pawn, which would secure a decisive advantage.} Ba6 13. Bc4 Bxb5 14. Bxb5 Nxc2 15. Rb1 {The dust has settled, and it should be visible that White is much better here. The bishop pair along with the annoying pressure on the d7 square are significant factors here. The h rook might be activated via e1  (after something like g3 , Kg2 ) or through h3  (after h2 - h4 ).} *

