1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxd5 {Definitely not a sound idea for Black. Provoking White to recapture with the pawn and gain a valuable tempo on the knight will likely backfire.} 6. exd5 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Qe7+ 8. Qe2 Bxd2+ 9. Kxd2 {Let's face it. I made this course for the fancy king moves. The rest is just a bonus. Jokes aside, the endgame is around the corner, so it makes perfect sense to centralize his majesty and vacate e1 for one of the rooks. We have seen similar positions in the previous chapter.} Qxe2+ 10. Bxe2 {White enjoys space advantage, and the d -pawn will soon be recaptured. On top of that, there is a significant development lead and the possibility of putting the rooks on central files. Undoubtedly, it's much easier to play this position with White.} Nb4 11. Rhe1 ({Another game saw} 11. Bc4 {( d6⩲ As usual, this pawn sacrifice deserves considerations.)} O-O 12. Nxd4 c6 13. d6 {With full positional domination in 1-0 Kostic, V (2455)-Schoellmann, J (2245) Bayern 2002.}) 11... Nxd5 {I don't think this is a good idea. Considering that White is ready to play Bc4 with a discovered check, Black is asking for trouble.} 12. Bc4+ Ne7 13. Re2 {White prepares the other rook to join the attack by coming to e1 .} Kf8 14. Rae1 {White threatens to win the knight. Please note that Black's back rank is also weak.} d5 15. Rxe7 Be6 16. Rxc7 dxc4 17. Nxd4 *

