1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxd5 {Definitely not a sound idea for Black. Provoking White to recapture with the pawn and gain a valuable tempo on the knight will likely backfire.} 6. exd5 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Qe7+ 8. Qe2 Bxd2+ 9. Kxd2 {Let's face it. I made this course for the fancy king moves. The rest is just a bonus. Jokes aside, the endgame is around the corner, so it makes perfect sense to centralize his majesty and vacate e1 for one of the rooks. We have seen similar positions in the previous chapter.} Qxe2+ 10. Bxe2 {White enjoys space advantage, and the d -pawn will soon be recaptured. On top of that, there is a significant development lead and the possibility of putting the rooks on central files. Undoubtedly, it's much easier to play this position with White.} Nb4 11. Rhe1 ({Another game saw} 11. Bc4 {( d6⩲ As usual, this pawn sacrifice deserves considerations.)} O-O 12. Nxd4 c6 13. d6 {With full positional domination in 1-0 Kostic, V (2455)-Schoellmann, J (2245) Bayern 2002.}) 11... O-O 12. d6 c5 {This position occurred in the game of young GM Peter Svidler; Svidler, P (2480)-Georg, H (2230) Dortmund 1991. At this point, Svidler should have played:} 13. Ne5 {The knight is placed on a fantastic spot. Together with the bishop, which is about to be placed on c4 , it will threaten the f7 pawn.} Rb8 {Black anticipates Bc4 after which b7 - b5 will be played.} 14. Bf3 b5 {Black dreams about playing Bb7 but as long as the knight hits d7 , it's a no-go.} 15. a3 Na6 16. a4 {Once more, White is attempting to paralyze Black's queenside, this time by fixing the pawn structure there.} bxa4 17. Rxa4 Rxb2 18. Bd5 {Threatening Nxf7 . Black's position has been divided into two parts. The left one doesn't even know about the existence of the right one and vice versa.} *

