1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxd5 {Definitely not a sound idea for Black. Provoking White to recapture with the pawn and gain a valuable tempo on the knight will likely backfire.} 6. exd5 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Qe7+ 8. Qe2 Bxd2+ 9. Kxd2 {Let's face it. I made this course for the fancy king moves. The rest is just a bonus. Jokes aside, the endgame is around the corner, so it makes perfect sense to centralize his majesty and vacate e1 for one of the rooks. We have seen similar positions in the previous chapter.} Qxe2+ 10. Bxe2 {White enjoys space advantage, and the d -pawn will soon be recaptured. On top of that, there is a significant development lead and the possibility of putting the rooks on central files. Undoubtedly, it's much easier to play this position with White.} Ne7 11. d6 {We've seen a similar motive before and it definitely constitutes one of the most important strategic resources in queenless lines of the Belgrade Gambit. The temporary pawn sacrifice is in fact an investment. White will most likely grab the d4 pawn back and next go after the d6 one. The resulting pawn structure will be highly favorable for White due to the d7 isolani.} cxd6 12. Nxd4 a6 {The bishop on c8 looks very shy.} 13. Rhe1 Kd8 {The Black king marches to c7 to seek refuge. It will actually be a good spot for the king as the d6 pawn needs to be protected.} 14. Bf3 {It's essential not to allow b7 - b5 with development of the bishop from c8 .} g6 {This position was seen in Chuprov, D (2531) -Kobylsky, E (2059) Samara 2011.} 15. Rad1 {White may put the king on c3 in a moment (or c1 if you prefer the safer approach), and then the rook from d1 will soon be activated.} (15. Re2 $6 Nc6 16. Kc3 Re8 17. Rae1 {1-0 Chuprov, D (2531) Kobylsky, E (2059) Samara 2011 The computer says it's equal, but I still prefer White for the ease of the next moves. Feel free to play a4 and possibly b4 . Pawn expansion on kingside may also be sound.}) 15... Nc6 16. Kc3 ({In another game, GM Sychev proposed a way to obtain an advantage. Yet, somehow he managed to lose. Kc7} 16. g3 Rf8 17. Ne2 Re8 18. Nf4 {This beautiful manoeuvre gave the knight access to pivotal} d5 {square. Positionally, Black is busted.} 19. Re5 {Nd5+ Kd8 Nb6} Rb8 {Nc4 Rc5 0-1 Sychev, K (2556) -Abdurakhmonov, M (2249) chess. com INT 2021 The Russian GM should have played: Bxc6± With a nice advantage as the d6 pawn falls and White maintains initiative.}) *

