1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxe4 {Clearly the most testing move. Black captures the second pawn hoping that White's initiative will not develop fast enough. This used to be the main theory for many years but nowadays people playing with Black generally try less risky options. The majority of players will dismiss this option due to 6. Qe2 lines - they do look scary, even though the current state of opening theory shows that 6. Qe2 doesn't promise White much.} 6. Bd3 {A rather innovative approach, which is very much in my taste. White simply develops the bishop, castling will come next and White will attempt to launch an attack on the kingside.} (6. Qe2 f5 7. Ng5 d3 $1 {as you may recall from the introduction, this move enables Black to get a good game.} 8. cxd3 Nd4 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qh4 c6 11. dxe4 cxd5 12. exd5 Bg7 {this position doesn't appeal to me, to be honest. White was supposed to have a lead in development and the safer king.}) 6... Nf6 {Technically speaking, this move is possible but it just seems weaker.} 7. Qe2+ Be7 8. Nxf6+ gxf6 {Black is up 2 pawns but his pawn structure on the kingside is bad. Logically, Black should try to castle queenside now. Having that in mind, we need to try playing actively and don't allow Black to safeguard his king. At least not for free.} 9. Bh6 {An interesting alternative, which looks dangerous. However, considering that Black is unlikely to castle kingside anyway, it may not be as strong as it seems at first glance. We may need this bishop on queenside.} d5 {Black's best approach is to develop queenside as fast as possible.} 10. O-O-O (10. Bg7 $2 {tempting but a waste of time.} Rg8 11. Bxf6 Kf8 {Black takes over the initiative. I know, it's hard to believe that. The g2 pawn is about to fall and White's attack perishes.}) 10... Rg8 11. Bf4 {The h7 pawn is under attack now. If it falls, White's h passed pawn will be a long-term asset. The other idea is to play Bb5 followed by Nxd4 .} (11. Bxh7 $2 {unfortunately, this just doesn't work.} Rh8 {White's bishops are in jeopardy.} 12. Qd3 Nb4 {White cannot protect the bishop.}) 11... Rxg2 {Way too greedy.} 12. Rdg1 {White wins the control over g file, which essentially means that Rg8 will be a massive threat.} Rg6 {Trying to sacrifice the exchange for the sake of safety and improvement of the pawn structure.} 13. h4 {Fortunately, capturing in chess is not mandatory. White wants to play h4 - h5 enforcing the exchange of rooks and preparing infiltration via Black's back rank. Despite the 3 pawns advantage, Black's position is much worse.} *

