1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxe4 {Clearly the most testing move. Black captures the second pawn hoping that White's initiative will not develop fast enough. This used to be the main theory for many years but nowadays people playing with Black generally try less risky options. The majority of players will dismiss this option due to 6. Qe2 lines - they do look scary, even though the current state of opening theory shows that 6. Qe2 doesn't promise White much.} 6. Bd3 {A rather innovative approach, which is very much in my taste. White simply develops the bishop, castling will come next and White will attempt to launch an attack on the kingside.} (6. Qe2 f5 7. Ng5 d3 $1 {as you may recall from the introduction, this move enables Black to get a good game.} 8. cxd3 Nd4 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qh4 c6 11. dxe4 cxd5 12. exd5 Bg7 {this position doesn't appeal to me, to be honest. White was supposed to have a lead in development and the safer king.}) 6... Nf6 {Technically speaking, this move is possible but it just seems weaker.} 7. Qe2+ Be7 8. Nxf6+ gxf6 {Black is up 2 pawns but his pawn structure on the kingside is bad. Logically, Black should try to castle queenside now. Having that in mind, we need to try playing actively and don't allow Black to safeguard his king. At least not for free.} 9. O-O {This is my preferred choice. It proves that generally Bb5 idea followed by winning the d pawn is more dangerous than the immediate action on kingside with Bh6 . Feel free to test both of those move and pick your favorite.} d5 10. Bb5 {White has a simple purpose: take on c6 to demolish Black's pawn formation and ensure that the Black king will never find refuge. Let's see what happens if Black tries to keep the original pawn structure.} Bd7 11. Re1 {It becomes evident that Black's position is really passive. The pin along the e file is really awkward. One idea is to trade on c6 and then take on d4 with a knight, threatening Nf5 . The other one is Bh6 - g7 - f6 winning the f6 pawn with annoying pressure.} a6 12. Bxc6 Bxc6 13. Nxd4 Bd7 14. Bf4 {Oh, and there is the third one! White threatens Bxc7 with a decoy.} Rc8 15. Qh5 {That's the dream. Black's king is still in the centre, and all of White's pieces are engaged in the attack. Well, the a1 rook is actually not attacking, but it soon will, either after a double-up along the e-file or the simple Rd1 move. I honestly don't know how Black is supposed to defend this. Perhaps ... O-O is the best try, but realistically, it should lead to a devastating attack.} *

