1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxe4 {Clearly the most testing move. Black captures the second pawn hoping that White's initiative will not develop fast enough. This used to be the main theory for many years but nowadays people playing with Black generally try less risky options. The majority of players will dismiss this option due to 6. Qe2 lines - they do look scary, even though the current state of opening theory shows that 6. Qe2 doesn't promise White much.} 6. Bd3 {A rather innovative approach, which is very much in my taste. White simply develops the bishop, castling will come next and White will attempt to launch an attack on the kingside.} (6. Qe2 f5 7. Ng5 d3 $1 {as you may recall from the introduction, this move enables Black to get a good game.} 8. cxd3 Nd4 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qh4 c6 11. dxe4 cxd5 12. exd5 Bg7 {this position doesn't appeal to me, to be honest. White was supposed to have a lead in development and the safer king.}) 6... Nf6 {Technically speaking, this move is possible but it just seems weaker.} 7. Qe2+ Be7 8. Nxf6+ gxf6 {Black is up 2 pawns but his pawn structure on the kingside is bad. Logically, Black should try to castle queenside now. Having that in mind, we need to try playing actively and don't allow Black to safeguard his king. At least not for free.} 9. O-O {This is my preferred choice. It proves that generally Bb5 idea followed by winning the d pawn is more dangerous than the immediate action on kingside with Bh6 . Feel free to test both of those move and pick your favorite.} d5 10. Bb5 {White has a simple purpose: take on c6 to demolish Black's pawn formation and ensure that the Black king will never find refuge.} Bg4 11. Re1 Qd7 {1/2 Monpeurt,C (2112) -Kassis,A (2189) Saint Quentin 2015.} 12. Bf4 {Thanks to the bishop pair and the much better pawn structure, White has a terrific compensation. CLICKABLE Let's take a look at a sample, logical line:} Bxf3 {Black captures on f3 in order to be able to castle.} 13. Qxf3 O-O-O 14. Rad1 {Hitting the d pawn once more. The key to understanding this position is that Black's pawn formation is so bad (particularly the f pawns), that Black does not really have a pawn advantage as none of the pawns on the kingside is not worth a full point.} h5 15. Rxd4 Bc5 16. Rd3 Qf5 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Bd2 {Surprisingly, Black has a difficult choice to make. Keeping the queens on the board means that White may be able to get the initiative on queenside and possibly start attacking c6 . The endgame will not be pleasant either as the f6 pawn could easily be attacked with the rook on f3 . Shifting the rook to c3 may also be a good idea in some lines to skewer the pawn on c6 . White is better according to the engine. My evaluation is a bit more restrained: White has full compensation for the pawn and good practical chances for more than a draw.} *

