1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxe4 {Clearly the most testing move. Black captures the second pawn hoping that White's initiative will not develop fast enough. This used to be the main theory for many years but nowadays people playing with Black generally try less risky options. The majority of players will dismiss this option due to 6. Qe2 lines - they do look scary, even though the current state of opening theory shows that 6. Qe2 doesn't promise White much.} 6. Bd3 {A rather innovative approach, which is very much in my taste. White simply develops the bishop, castling will come next and White will attempt to launch an attack on the kingside.} (6. Qe2 f5 7. Ng5 d3 $1 {as you may recall from the introduction, this move enables Black to get a good game.} 8. cxd3 Nd4 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qh4 c6 11. dxe4 cxd5 12. exd5 Bg7 {this position doesn't appeal to me, to be honest. White was supposed to have a lead in development and the safer king.}) {This strange-looking continuation was once tried against the humble author.} 6... f5 7. O-O Bd6 8. Bxe4 fxe4 9. Bg5 {It turns out that Black's setup isn't flawless as the queen is in danger.} Ne7 10. Qxd4 O-O 11. Qxe4 {The pin along the h4 - d8 diagonal is crushing.} Rf7 12. Rfe1 Kf8 13. Qxh7 {Black had enough. Normal 1-0 (13) AttackingBeast (2767)-SlimFritz (2767) lichess.org 2022} *

