1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxe4 {Clearly the most testing move. Black captures the second pawn hoping that White's initiative will not develop fast enough. This used to be the main theory for many years but nowadays people playing with Black generally try less risky options. The majority of players will dismiss this option due to 6. Qe2 lines - they do look scary, even though the current state of opening theory shows that 6. Qe2 doesn't promise White much.} 6. Bd3 {A rather innovative approach, which is very much in my taste. White simply develops the bishop, castling will come next and White will attempt to launch an attack on the kingside.} (6. Qe2 f5 7. Ng5 d3 $1 {as you may recall from the introduction, this move enables Black to get a good game.} 8. cxd3 Nd4 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qh4 c6 11. dxe4 cxd5 12. exd5 Bg7 {this position doesn't appeal to me, to be honest. White was supposed to have a lead in development and the safer king.}) 6... Nc5 {Black attacks the bishop on d3 , which is often a useful attacking piece. It makes perfect sense to prepare the possibility of exchanging minor pieces as well.} 7. O-O Be7 8. Re1 (8. Re1 Ne6 {this is Black's only move. We will see it analyzed via 7... Ne6 move order.}) 8... O-O {The following continuation is the reason for me falling in love with this opening!} 9. Nxe7+ Nxe7 10. Bxh7+ {Bang! The classic bishop sacrifice is always trendy. White is already busted.} Kxh7 11. Ng5+ Kg6 {Usually, this is the only hope for the defender if it's impossible to cover h7 square.} 12. Qg4 {Not going into details, Black is in grave danger. Giving back the material will probably be necessary to survive. Currently Ne6 winning the queen is the threat.} f5 13. Qg3 Kf6 14. Qh4 {Threatening Ne6 and Qxd4 .} Rh8 15. Qxd4+ Kg6 16. Qxc5 {The material is equal but Black is unlikely to survive the attack with such a poor king placement.} *

