1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxe4 {Clearly the most testing move. Black captures the second pawn hoping that White's initiative will not develop fast enough. This used to be the main theory for many years but nowadays people playing with Black generally try less risky options. The majority of players will dismiss this option due to 6. Qe2 lines - they do look scary, even though the current state of opening theory shows that 6. Qe2 doesn't promise White much.} 6. Bd3 {A rather innovative approach, which is very much in my taste. White simply develops the bishop, castling will come next and White will attempt to launch an attack on the kingside.} (6. Qe2 f5 7. Ng5 d3 $1 {as you may recall from the introduction, this move enables Black to get a good game.} 8. cxd3 Nd4 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qh4 c6 11. dxe4 cxd5 12. exd5 Bg7 {this position doesn't appeal to me, to be honest. White was supposed to have a lead in development and the safer king.}) 6... Nc5 {Black attacks the bishop on d3 , which is often a useful attacking piece. It makes perfect sense to prepare the possibility of exchanging minor pieces as well.} 7. O-O Nxd3 {Premature as the knight has a defensive duty on e6 while the Black king is still in the centre of the board.} 8. Qxd3 Bc5 {Black should really learn about the priortities in chess. The d pawn is irrelevant considering the vulnerability of Black's king in the middle of the board.} 9. Re1+ Kf8 10. Bg5 f6 11. Nxf6 {There's no time to be wasted here. White takes advantage of the lead in development and crushes through.} gxf6 12. Bh6+ Kg8 13. Nxd4 {Another piece sacrifice. Actually, this time Black can't take the piece due to Qg3 followed by Qg7 checkmate.} Bf8 14. Qg3+ Kf7 15. Qf3 {Possibly there are other moves but Black prepared Rg8 in order to defend the king. White switches the plan to attacking on light squares. Let's take a look at a few possible lines.} d5 16. Qh5+ Kg8 17. Re8 {Black is completely outplayed here due to the attack on the queen and bishop.} *

