1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxe4 {Clearly the most testing move. Black captures the second pawn hoping that White's initiative will not develop fast enough. This used to be the main theory for many years but nowadays people playing with Black generally try less risky options. The majority of players will dismiss this option due to 6. Qe2 lines - they do look scary, even though the current state of opening theory shows that 6. Qe2 doesn't promise White much.} 6. Bd3 {A rather innovative approach, which is very much in my taste. White simply develops the bishop, castling will come next and White will attempt to launch an attack on the kingside.} (6. Qe2 f5 7. Ng5 d3 $1 {as you may recall from the introduction, this move enables Black to get a good game.} 8. cxd3 Nd4 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qh4 c6 11. dxe4 cxd5 12. exd5 Bg7 {this position doesn't appeal to me, to be honest. White was supposed to have a lead in development and the safer king.}) 6... Nc5 {Black attacks the bishop on d3 , which is often a useful attacking piece. It makes perfect sense to prepare the possibility of exchanging minor pieces as well.} 7. O-O Nxd3 {Premature as the knight has a defensive duty on e6 while the Black king is still in the centre of the board.} 8. Qxd3 Be7 9. Nxd4 O-O 10. Re1 {Threatening Nxc6 followed by Nxe7 winning a piece.} Bc5 11. Nf3 {White still has an initiative despite the lack of the light-squared bishop. One of the minor pieces is about to go to g5 with annoying attack. Here it's really easy to go wrong.} Nb4 {From Black's perspective, it probably makes more sense to exchange the knights to keep the game simpler.} 12. Nxb4 Bxb4 13. Bg5 {Forcing a favourable sequence of moves.} f6 14. Qc4+ d5 15. Qxb4 fxg5 16. Re7 Rf4 17. Qc5 {Remmber that the queen is supposed to protect the rook. Luckily, it can also attack c7 pawn.} Bf5 18. Rae1 {White keeps a nice pressure along the 7th rank as well as threatens Nxg5 .} *

