1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxe4 {Clearly the most testing move. Black captures the second pawn hoping that White's initiative will not develop fast enough. This used to be the main theory for many years but nowadays people playing with Black generally try less risky options. The majority of players will dismiss this option due to 6. Qe2 lines - they do look scary, even though the current state of opening theory shows that 6. Qe2 doesn't promise White much.} 6. Bd3 {A rather innovative approach, which is very much in my taste. White simply develops the bishop, castling will come next and White will attempt to launch an attack on the kingside.} (6. Qe2 f5 7. Ng5 d3 $1 {as you may recall from the introduction, this move enables Black to get a good game.} 8. cxd3 Nd4 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qh4 c6 11. dxe4 cxd5 12. exd5 Bg7 {this position doesn't appeal to me, to be honest. White was supposed to have a lead in development and the safer king.}) 6... Nc5 {Black attacks the bishop on d3 , which is often a useful attacking piece. It makes perfect sense to prepare the possibility of exchanging minor pieces as well.} 7. O-O Ne6 {This move was played in a high profile game: Guerra Bastida-Korneev, 2000. It was played over 20 years ago, but it's still relevant from the point of the opening theory. The game saw the interesting} 8. c3 {One of the main purposes of this move is to clear the b1 - h7 diagonal for the queen.} dxc3 9. bxc3 Bc5 10. Re1 O-O 11. Bxh7+ {Black faces serious shelling.} Kxh7 12. Ng5+ {Guerra Bastida, who was a clear underdog, continued in a very inspired fashion. It was necessary to play:} Nxg5 13. Qh5+ Kg8 14. Bxg5 f6 {the only move} 15. Bxf6 {In for a penny, out for a pound. White cannot slow down at this point.} Rxf6 16. Re8+ Qxe8 {This move shows how easy it was to miss the subtle tactical nuances in the calculation process.} 17. Nxf6+ gxf6 18. Qxe8+ *

