1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxe4 {Clearly the most testing move. Black captures the second pawn hoping that White's initiative will not develop fast enough. This used to be the main theory for many years but nowadays people playing with Black generally try less risky options. The majority of players will dismiss this option due to 6. Qe2 lines - they do look scary, even though the current state of opening theory shows that 6. Qe2 doesn't promise White much.} 6. Bd3 {A rather innovative approach, which is very much in my taste. White simply develops the bishop, castling will come next and White will attempt to launch an attack on the kingside.} (6. Qe2 f5 7. Ng5 d3 $1 {as you may recall from the introduction, this move enables Black to get a good game.} 8. cxd3 Nd4 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qh4 c6 11. dxe4 cxd5 12. exd5 Bg7 {this position doesn't appeal to me, to be honest. White was supposed to have a lead in development and the safer king.}) 6... Nc5 {Black attacks the bishop on d3 , which is often a useful attacking piece. It makes perfect sense to prepare the possibility of exchanging minor pieces as well.} 7. O-O Ne6 {This move was played in a high profile game: Guerra Bastida-Korneev, 2000. It was played over 20 years ago, but it's still relevant from the point of the opening theory.} 8. Re1 Be7 {A very natural continuation.} 9. h4 {The key move! White increases the control over g5 square, which will be used by one of the minor pieces. Delaying to castle should be directly met with:} d6 10. b4 {Preparing b4 - b5 ideas and possibly the development of the bishop to b2 if needed.} a6 11. Ng5 {White approaches Black's kingside. Capturing the knight on g5 is probably not a good idea for Black as both the bishop on e7 and the knight on e6 should protect the king. White may also try to play f4 - f5 .} Ne5 12. Nxe7 Qxe7 13. f4 Nxd3 14. Qxd3 {Transposes.} *

