1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxe4 {Clearly the most testing move. Black captures the second pawn hoping that White's initiative will not develop fast enough. This used to be the main theory for many years but nowadays people playing with Black generally try less risky options. The majority of players will dismiss this option due to 6. Qe2 lines - they do look scary, even though the current state of opening theory shows that 6. Qe2 doesn't promise White much.} 6. Bd3 {A rather innovative approach, which is very much in my taste. White simply develops the bishop, castling will come next and White will attempt to launch an attack on the kingside.} (6. Qe2 f5 7. Ng5 d3 $1 {as you may recall from the introduction, this move enables Black to get a good game.} 8. cxd3 Nd4 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qh4 c6 11. dxe4 cxd5 12. exd5 Bg7 {this position doesn't appeal to me, to be honest. White was supposed to have a lead in development and the safer king.}) 6... Nc5 {Black attacks the bishop on d3 , which is often a useful attacking piece. It makes perfect sense to prepare the possibility of exchanging minor pieces as well.} 7. O-O Ne6 {This move was played in a high profile game: Guerra Bastida-Korneev, 2000. It was played over 20 years ago, but it's still relevant from the point of the opening theory.} 8. Re1 Be7 {A very natural continuation.} 9. h4 {The key move! White increases the control over g5 square, which will be used by one of the minor pieces.} O-O 10. Ng5 {Once more White manages to utilize the pawn on h4 by planting the knight on g5 .} f5 {Quite a logical idea for Black as it restricts the bishop on d3 .} 11. Qh5 Nxg5 {This loses by force and I mean by force.} 12. Nxe7+ Nxe7 13. Bxg5 Rf7 14. Bxe7 Rxe7 15. Qxf5 g6 16. Qd5+ {Black does not have sufficient defensive resources.} Kg7 17. Qxd4+ Kg8 18. Bc4+ {Black will lose material or get mated soon.} *

