1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxe4 {Clearly the most testing move. Black captures the second pawn hoping that White's initiative will not develop fast enough. This used to be the main theory for many years but nowadays people playing with Black generally try less risky options. The majority of players will dismiss this option due to 6. Qe2 lines - they do look scary, even though the current state of opening theory shows that 6. Qe2 doesn't promise White much.} 6. Bd3 {A rather innovative approach, which is very much in my taste. White simply develops the bishop, castling will come next and White will attempt to launch an attack on the kingside.} (6. Qe2 f5 7. Ng5 d3 $1 {as you may recall from the introduction, this move enables Black to get a good game.} 8. cxd3 Nd4 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qh4 c6 11. dxe4 cxd5 12. exd5 Bg7 {this position doesn't appeal to me, to be honest. White was supposed to have a lead in development and the safer king.}) 6... Nc5 {Black attacks the bishop on d3 , which is often a useful attacking piece. It makes perfect sense to prepare the possibility of exchanging minor pieces as well.} 7. O-O Ne6 {This move was played in a high profile game: Guerra Bastida-Korneev, 2000. It was played over 20 years ago, but it's still relevant from the point of the opening theory.} 8. Re1 h6 {Black may try to prevent a White minor piece coming to g5 . It looks like a violation of opening principles but Black is up 2 pawns and unfortunately, his position is quite solid. A word of introduction: this time the Bd2 and c2 - c3 setup is less effective as Black can develop with g7 - g6 followed by Bg7 fighting for that diagonal.} 9. Bf4 d6 {Virtually forced as the c7 pawn was under attack.} 10. Bg3 {White intends to play Nh4 followed by Qh5 with an attack on kingside. At this point Black has 2 reasonable options.} Ne7 {This time Black tries to get rid of our powerful centralized horse.} 11. Nf4 {I like the concept of trading the pieces on our own terms. Black's knight is very useful on e6 as it efficiently blocks any immediate action on e file. Naturally, Black prefers to exchange the other knight to develop the bishop to e7 next. Fortunately, we don't have to cooperate with Black.} Nxf4 {Otherwise, the possibility of exchanging may be gone forever. Especially after something like Nf4 - h5 hitting g7 .} 12. Bxf4 g5 {Black is well-advised to play forcefully here. This is the only way to protect the d4 pawn by developing the bishop to g7 quickly. It's not a human way of handling this position, but it is a way.} 13. Bg3 (13. Bxg5 {, the engine suggests such a creative way of proceeding here. Perhaps it could be tried with more in-depth analysis. However, it seems to be too chaotic for my taste.} hxg5 14. Nxg5 Rh6 15. Qf3 f6 16. Ne6 Bxe6 17. Rxe6 Kf7 18. Rae1 {Apparently, White has full compensation for the piece. I don't fully understand it, but the engine does. Based on its suggestions, the g4-g5 idea is very strong and promises White a dangerous attack.}) 13... Bg7 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 {It's important to understand why it's not so dangerous.} 15. Bb5+ Bd7 16. Qxd4 {White recaptures the piece and attacks the rook on h8 .} O-O 17. Bd3 {In human terms, it looks much better for White. After all, Black has an exposed king, a suspicious pawn structure and less active pieces. According to the engine, it's equal. Considering Black's pawn advantage, it's his way of saying that White has full compensation for the pawn, but not more than that. I like White's chances in long perspective, mainly as White's position just looks much easier to play, but all results are possible. Most likely, we should be looking for ways to challenge Black's kingside pawn formation with h2 - h4 . Simple activation of the rook on a1 is a natural way to proceed, as well.} *

