1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxe4 {Clearly the most testing move. Black captures the second pawn hoping that White's initiative will not develop fast enough. This used to be the main theory for many years but nowadays people playing with Black generally try less risky options. The majority of players will dismiss this option due to 6. Qe2 lines - they do look scary, even though the current state of opening theory shows that 6. Qe2 doesn't promise White much.} 6. Bd3 {A rather innovative approach, which is very much in my taste. White simply develops the bishop, castling will come next and White will attempt to launch an attack on the kingside.} (6. Qe2 f5 7. Ng5 d3 $1 {as you may recall from the introduction, this move enables Black to get a good game.} 8. cxd3 Nd4 9. Qh5+ g6 10. Qh4 c6 11. dxe4 cxd5 12. exd5 Bg7 {this position doesn't appeal to me, to be honest. White was supposed to have a lead in development and the safer king.}) 6... Nc5 {Black attacks the bishop on d3 , which is often a useful attacking piece. It makes perfect sense to prepare the possibility of exchanging minor pieces as well.} 7. O-O Ne6 {This move was played in a high profile game: Guerra Bastida-Korneev, 2000. It was played over 20 years ago, but it's still relevant from the point of the opening theory.} 8. Re1 d6 {This is a very reasonable move. Black activates the bishop. White has several options here. I will leave the choice to you.} 9. Bb5 {Intending to take on d4 and exert pressure along the e file and a4 - e8 diagonal at the same time.} Bd7 10. Bg5 {This looks really scary for Black. Imagine having to defend this: on each move you need to calculate multiple forcing continuations. In a practical game, it's an extremely difficult task.} Ne7 (10... Be7 11. Bxc6 {we're entering a forced sequence of moves, where Black needs to play precisely in order to avoid material loss.} Bxg5 {obviously the only move as otherwise White wins the bishop on e7 .} 12. Bxd7+ ({(} 12. Bxb7 $6 Rb8 13. Nxg5 ({(But then the computer shocked me with: O-O! White is unable to keep everything protected and the best line leads to a perpetual check. Nxh7 Kxh7 Qh5+ Kg8} 13. Ba6 c6 {The knight is trapped! White saves the game with a creative attack.} 14. Bd3 g6 {Qh6 cxd5} 15. Rxe6+ Bxe6 16. Bxg6 fxg6 {Qxg6+ Kh8 Qh6+= Draw by perpetual check.)}) 13... Qxg5 $2 {this gives White a clear positional edge.} 14. Nxc7+ Kd8 15. Nxe6+ fxe6 16. Be4 {White enjoys a solid plus due to Black's king position. )}) 12... Kxd7 ({(} 12... Qxd7 $4 13. Nxg5 {White is up a piece.)}) {The only move but a good one. Objectively, it will not be easy to take advantage of Black's king position.} 13. Nxd4 {White has a compensation for the pawn, but probably not more than that.}) 11. Bd3 h6 12. Bxe7 (12. Bf6 $6 {That's a funny trap, but noone will fall for it.} gxf6 {c6 It's probably enough to kick White's pieces back one by one.} 13. Nxf6# {That's one sweet checkmate!}) 12... Bxe7 13. Nxd4 O-O 14. Qg4 {Majority of White's pieces is engaged in the attack. The next move may be Qe4 .} Nxd4 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Qxd4 (16. Rxe7 $4 {not good as we lose our queen, too.} Bxg4 {.}) 16... Qg5 17. Qe4 g6 18. Qxb7 {The game is on but the most likely result is definitely a draw. White may still have microscopically better chances due to the better pawn formation.} *

