1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... c6 {This continuation lets White take over the initiative.} (6... Nfxd5 {Black is given a chance to capture with the wrong knight and transition to the 5... Nxd5 chapter.} 7. exd5 {transposes to 5...Nxd5.}) 7. Nxf6+ Qxf6 8. Bg5 Qg6 9. O-O {The opening phase of the game was a massive success for White. The development of minor pieces is finished, the king is safe, the situation in the centre looks more than ok. White still has realistic chances of winning the d pawn back. The next move will probably be a3 . Black's task is far more difficult.} *

