1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Qe7+ {One of Black's main moves here, although probably not the best one.} 8. Kf1 {Pretty much forced in case White wishes to fight for an opening edge. On the other hand, by now you have already seen this move a couple of times. Consider this preparation to transfer the rook from a1 to e1 in a few moves and you'll actually be happy to see Black forcing you to move the king.} Qc5 {Black needs to introduce the bishop into play, so winning the tempo on our bishop makes perfect sense here.} 9. Qxd4 {Practically forced. I wish I could only present fun lines with the queens on the board, but this is the reality. Fortunately, White still has a few aces up the sleeve.} Qxd4 10. Nxd4 Bc5 11. Nb3 Bb6 {It doesn't seem precise.} 12. a4 {Preparing to trap the bishop with a4 - a5 and soften Black's pawn structure.} a5 13. d6 {Strong as always!} cxd6 14. Bg5 {White has much better prospects here. The bishop on c8 is permanently out of play. White's rook will come to e1 in a moment and if needed, you may even wish to capture on f6 to play Bd5 and paralyze Black.} *

