1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bc5 {The position is almost symmetric, but the d4 pawn is already attacked and the bishop on c1 is about to be activated. Ironically, there will be positions, when taking on d4 will not be advisable as it will only increase the scope of the Black bishop on c5 .} 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5 {Let's see what happens if Black follows the most natural sequence of moves aimed at getting rid of the pin.} h6 10. Bh4 g5 11. Nxg5 hxg5 12. Bxg5 Be7 {In this position I played the typical Belgrade Gambit idea.} 13. Re1 {According to the engine, this is even stronger. White's next move is Qf3 threatening Rxe7 .} *


