1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bc5 {The position is almost symmetric, but the d4 pawn is already attacked and the bishop on c1 is about to be activated. Ironically, there will be positions, when taking on d4 will not be advisable as it will only increase the scope of the Black bishop on c5 .} 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5 d6 10. h3 {The d4 pawn will not escape and it's worth playing a few prophylactic moves. First of all, the Black bishop is not to be allowed on g4 .} Re8 11. Bd3 {I like this subtle multipurpose move. The bishop on c8 is deprived of the f5 square, so its options are limited with every single move. More importantly, White's light-square bishop is not restricted by the d5 anymore. The plan is simple: Qd2 followed by Qf4 with pressure on f6 and d4 .} h6 12. Bh4 c6 13. Re1 {This move made a huge impression on me. It's the engine's top choice, which demonstrates that the strength of the pawns is not always related to their number.   White is ready to give up yet another pawn in order to pressurize Black without losing a single tempo. Can you feel the wind in your hair? Life is beautiful.} cxd5 {Let's see where this is going.} 14. Bxf6 Rxe1+ 15. Qxe1 Qxf6 {Loses on spot.} 16. Qe8# *

