1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bc5 {The position is almost symmetric, but the d4 pawn is already attacked and the bishop on c1 is about to be activated. Ironically, there will be positions, when taking on d4 will not be advisable as it will only increase the scope of the Black bishop on c5 .} 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5 d6 10. h3 {The d4 pawn will not escape and it's worth playing a few prophylactic moves. First of all, the Black bishop is not to be allowed on g4 .} Bf5 {Probably the better setup for Black. Clearly, the bishop on c8 is misplaced and it should be developed rather quickly. Otherwise, White just brings the bishop back to d3 .} 11. Re1 {By occupying the e file, White ensures that Black won't play Re8 .} Re8 12. Rxe8+ Qxe8 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Bd3 {There is no point in taking the d pawn, as explained earlier. It has no dynamic value. Instead, White should exchange the light-squared bishops in order to dominate light squares with the knight. White is much better due to better pawn structure and piece coordination. It's not even a matter of compensation for the material. White just doesn't need that pawn on d4 to be happy.} *

