1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bb4+ 8. Kf1 {Unfortunately, the right to castle is permanently lost. Well, at least until the next game. On a positive note, White will win the d pawn back. Typically, the rook from a1 will be moved to e1 .} Bc5 9. Qe1+ {What a clever check! Black has a difficult choice to make now.} Qe7 {Clearly the best.} 10. Bg5 {In this line, White's purpose is to double Black's pawns on f file.} Qxe1+ 11. Rxe1+ Kd8 {This just loses tactically.} 12. Ne5 {White threatens Nxf7 ; Ng4 or d5 - d6 will follow if Black defends the pawn.} *

