1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bb4+ 8. Kf1 {Unfortunately, the right to castle is permanently lost. Well, at least until the next game. On a positive note, White will win the d pawn back. Typically, the rook from a1 will be moved to e1 .} Bc5 9. Qe1+ {What a clever check! Black has a difficult choice to make now.} Qe7 {Clearly the best.} 10. Bg5 {In this line, White's purpose is to double Black's pawns on f file.} Qxe1+ 11. Rxe1+ Kf8 {The only move.} 12. Bxf6 {Demolishing Black's pawn formation.} gxf6 13. Rd1 ({White regains the pawn now. In return, Black gets the bishop pair, and the position is no longer obvious. One of White's ideas is to trade the light-squared bishops and transfer the h1 rook to f3 . Rg8} 13. Nxd4 {Rg4 Black chooses the right path to equality. c3} Bxd4 {cxd4 Ke7} 14. f3 {Rg6 Re1+ Kd6 Kf2} b6 15. Re4 $1 Bb7 16. Rh4 {The position is almost equal. White's best hope is connected to the possibility of winning the kingside pawns using the mighty rook. The d5 pawn may be protected with Rh5 or indirectly with Rc1 . Black still needs to work hard for a draw.}) *

