1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bb4+ 8. Kf1 {Unfortunately, the right to castle is permanently lost. Well, at least until the next game. On a positive note, White will win the d pawn back. Typically, the rook from a1 will be moved to e1 .} c5 {Black tries to hold on to the d -pawn.} 9. a3 Ba5 10. b4 {A critical idea aimed at breaking Black's c5 - d4 pawn formation. Opening new files and diagonals will be useful as well.} cxb4 {GM Sychev once successfully tried:} {1/2-1/2 Chereches, M (2268)-Papp, P (2246) Hungary 2010. White has a few interesting ideas, but according to GM Christian Bauer, axb4 is the strongest.} 11. Qe1+ Qe7 12. Bf4 Qxe1+ 13. Rxe1+ Kd8 14. Ng5 Rf8 15. Bd6 (15. axb4 Bxb4 {1-0 Sychev, K (2556)-Nasuta, G (2518) chess.com INT 2021. White eventually won the game after an entertaining battle.  The text move 15.Bd6 would have been cleaner.}) *

