1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bb4+ 8. Kf1 {Unfortunately, the right to castle is permanently lost. Well, at least until the next game. On a positive note, White will win the d pawn back. Typically, the rook from a1 will be moved to e1 .} c5 {Black tries to hold on to the d -pawn.} 9. a3 Ba5 10. b4 {A critical idea aimed at breaking Black's c5 - d4 pawn formation. Opening new files and diagonals will be useful as well.} cxb4 {1/2-1/2 Chereches, M (2268)-Papp, P (2246) Hungary 2010. White has a few interesting ideas, but according to GM Christian Bauer, axb4 is the strongest.} 11. axb4 Bxb4 12. Qxd4 Qe7 13. Bg5 {The king's placement is almost ideal. White threatens to play c2 - c3 followed by Re1 .} O-O 14. c3 Bc5 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. Qh4 {White's position is splendid. The h pawn is just waiting to be attacked with the bishop. another idea is Re1 - e4 - g4 .} *

