1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bb4+ 8. Kf1 {Unfortunately, the right to castle is permanently lost. Well, at least until the next game. On a positive note, White will win the d pawn back. Typically, the rook from a1 will be moved to e1 .} d6 {This time Black tries to open the other bishop. I don't think this is bright idea with the king still in the middle of the board but let's see where this is going.} 9. Qe2+ Kf8 {Someone is trying to copy our approach!} 10. Nxd4 {White simply takes on d4 in order to play Nb3 followed by c2 - c3 or a2 - a3 forcing the exchange of Black's bishop for the knight.} Bc5 11. Nb3 Bb6 12. a4 {The purpose of this advance is to gain space and soften Black's pawn structure on queenside.} a5 13. f3 {Once more, the purpose is to play g4 and Kg2 . This should enable connecting the rooks and improving overall piece coordination.} Bf5 14. Bf4 (14. g4 $2 Nxg4 $1 {Black gets access to our king.} 15. fxg4 Qh4 $1 {yet another piece?! Black sacrifices everything to deliver checkmate} 16. gxf5 Re8 {all of a sudden, it turns out that the queen is overloaded. It's impossible to protect c4 and f2 .} 17. Nd2 Rxe2 18. Kxe2 Qg4+ {Black keeps the dangerous attack, which will likely lead to White losing material.}) 14... Qe7 15. Qxe7+ Kxe7 16. c3 {It's important to escape from c2 with the pawn prior to g2 - g4 .} h5 17. h4 {The position is balanced but White may still try to push for a win. The king should be transferred to d2 to support queenside. The dark-squared bishop should go to g5 and the knight to d4 .} *

