1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bb4+ 8. Kf1 {Unfortunately, the right to castle is permanently lost. Well, at least until the next game. On a positive note, White will win the d pawn back. Typically, the rook from a1 will be moved to e1 .} d6 {This time Black tries to open the other bishop. I don't think this is bright idea with the king still in the middle of the board but let's see where this is going.} 9. Qe2+ Kf8 {Someone is trying to copy our approach!} 10. Nxd4 {White simply takes on d4 in order to play Nb3 followed by c2 - c3 or a2 - a3 forcing the exchange of Black's bishop for the knight.} Bc5 11. Nb3 Bb6 12. a4 {The purpose of this advance is to gain space and soften Black's pawn structure on queenside.} a6 13. a5 {Leading to more space and a fixed pawn structure in Black's camp. It should be easier to attack it later on.} Ba7 14. f3 {intending g4 and Kg2 .} Bf5 15. Bg5 {In a moment White will be able to play c2 - c3 and Nd4 or Re1 with good active play.} h5 16. h4 g6 {Logical but dubious.} 17. Qd2 Kg7 18. Nd4 {White managed to perform an illustrative rearrangement of the pieces. Black is likely to suffer on the dark squares.} *

