1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bb4+ 8. Kf1 {Unfortunately, the right to castle is permanently lost. Well, at least until the next game. On a positive note, White will win the d pawn back. Typically, the rook from a1 will be moved to e1 .} d6 {This time Black tries to open the other bishop. I don't think this is bright idea with the king still in the middle of the board but let's see where this is going.} 9. Qe2+ Qe7 10. Qxe7+ Kxe7 11. Nxd4 {intending Nb3 and a3 / c3 .} Bc5 {Necessary to keep the bishop.} 12. Nb3 Bb6 13. Bg5 {Pins are so powerful! White will play Re1 next.} Bd7 14. Re1+ Kf8 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. h4 {You’ve probably seen the h2 - h4 move throughout this course.   Typically, it is played in order to introduce the rook from h1 to play via h3 . This time, White’s main idea is a bit more subtle. We need to connect the rooks in order to improve the overall piece coordination.   However, the normal g2 - g3 followed by Kg2 will not suffice as g2 - g3 temporarily weakens the h3 square, allowing the nasty Bh3 +.   Consequently, before repositioning the king, White increases the control over h3 . The other concept is simply to push the h pawn to h6 , which will in turn fix the Black pawn on h7 and make it weaker in the context of the endgame.} Kg7 17. h5 {The pawn may go as far as h6 , while Rh4 - f4 is the other idea.} *

