1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bb4+ 8. Kf1 {Unfortunately, the right to castle is permanently lost. Well, at least until the next game. On a positive note, White will win the d pawn back. Typically, the rook from a1 will be moved to e1 .} O-O {Assuming that White doesn't even want to take the pawn in many instances, what's the point of protecting it? It is quite logical. I have to admit.} 9. Qxd4 Re8 {One of the best moves for Black.} 10. Bg5 Be7 11. h4 {I really like this concept. First and foremost, White safeguards the bishop on g5 . Further pawn march to h6 is also an option. There is also a strategic point: the possibility of developing the rook via h3 . Let me show you another idea worth remembering.} h6 12. Bd3 hxg5 {This leads to a disaster for Black.} 13. hxg5 {Black is not ready for opening of the h file. White's next move will probably be Qh4 looking for a checkmate.} *

