1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bb4+ 8. Kf1 {Unfortunately, the right to castle is permanently lost. Well, at least until the next game. On a positive note, White will win the d pawn back. Typically, the rook from a1 will be moved to e1 .} O-O {Assuming that White doesn't even want to take the pawn in many instances, what's the point of protecting it? It is quite logical. I have to admit.} 9. Qxd4 Re8 {One of the best moves for Black.} 10. Bg5 Be7 11. h4 {I really like this concept. First and foremost, White safeguards the bishop on g5 . Further pawn march to h6 is also an option. There is also a strategic point: the possibility of developing the rook via h3 .} d6 12. Bd3 {White's bishop hits h7 . Sometimes the simple improvement of a piece is what the position requires.} Bd7 {Let's see how the game may develop from here.} 13. Re1 h6 14. Qf4 {Remember this idea! White does not need to be afraid of losing the g5 bishop as opening the h file will be lethal. White prepares Nd4 - f5 idea.} Nh5 15. Qe4 {White threatens checkmate. We're already in the middlegame but I'd like to show you a couple of sample lines, which illustrate ideas for both sides. You definitely don't need to learn all of them. Just try to keep your mind open for such possibilities.} f5 16. Qb4 {The bishop on g5 is poisoned all the time!} a5 17. Qd2 {definitely not} Nf6 18. g3 {Preparing Kg2 with a healthy position.} Nxd5 19. Bxf5 {Hammer time! The knight on d5 is under attack.} *

