1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bb4+ 8. Kf1 {Unfortunately, the right to castle is permanently lost. Well, at least until the next game. On a positive note, White will win the d pawn back. Typically, the rook from a1 will be moved to e1 .} O-O {Assuming that White doesn't even want to take the pawn in many instances, what's the point of protecting it? It is quite logical. I have to admit.} 9. Qxd4 d6 {I don't really see how blocking the bishop from the posibility of defending the kingside might be a good idea. On the other hand, c5 seems like a perfect spot for the bishop now.} 10. Bd3 Bc5 11. Qh4 {White already puts pressure on h7 , effectively freezing the knight on f6 . In the near future, White's moves may include Bg5 or even g4 - g5 .} Re8 {Black occupies the open file, which may be a very important element of the defensive strategy.} 12. a4 {Engine's top choice, intending b2 - b4 .} a5 13. Rg1 {A really unique opening setup. White intends to play g2 - g4 - g5 .} h6 {It's investigate the direct approach:} 14. Bxh6 gxh6 15. g4 {This came out of nowhere. Instead of taking the h pawn, White will use it as a hook to open the g file. Remarkable!} Nxd5 16. Qxh6 {Now that the knight is no longer on f6 , we change the plans.} Qf6 17. Bh7+ Kh8 18. Bg6+ Kg8 19. Bh7+ Kh8 20. Bg6+ {Draw is the best we can get here even though it all looked very promising.} *

