1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bb4+ 8. Kf1 {Unfortunately, the right to castle is permanently lost. Well, at least until the next game. On a positive note, White will win the d pawn back. Typically, the rook from a1 will be moved to e1 .} O-O {Assuming that White doesn't even want to take the pawn in many instances, what's the point of protecting it? It is quite logical. I have to admit.} 9. Qxd4 {Another instructive game saw:} Be7 10. Bg5 d6 11. Re1 h6 {0-1 Van der Weide, K (2350) -Notkin,M (2465) Groningen 1994.} 12. h4 {This is my improvement over the stem game.} Bf5 13. g4 {In for a penny, out for a pound. Black shouldn't really take the pawn.} Bxc2 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Qd2 Bh7 16. g5 {White has realistic chances of opening the kingside by force. The caveman attack proved to be effective. Sometimes, the beauty is in simplicity.   Black has his own chances with the bishop pair but it's much easier to attack with White than to defend with Black. One important idea could be to play Bd3 to trade Black's king's defender for our passive bishop.} *

