1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bb4+ 8. Kf1 {Unfortunately, the right to castle is permanently lost. Well, at least until the next game. On a positive note, White will win the d pawn back. Typically, the rook from a1 will be moved to e1 .} O-O {Assuming that White doesn't even want to take the pawn in many instances, what's the point of protecting it? It is quite logical. I have to admit.} 9. Qxd4 {Another instructive game saw:} Be7 10. Bg5 d6 11. Re1 h6 {0-1 Van der Weide, K (2350) -Notkin,M (2465) Groningen 1994.} 12. h4 {This is my improvement over the stem game.} Bf5 13. g4 {In for a penny, out for a pound. Black shouldn't really take the pawn.} Bd7 14. Bd3 {We have a sort of a Mexican standoff here. White has just improved the bishop, which was simply restricted by the pawn on d5 and thus added a piece to the potential attack. Obviously, capturing on g5 is not recommended for Black as this would just unleash the beast (White's rook and bishop) after hxg5 . White should prepare to sacrifice on h6 at some point and simply push the g&h pawns forward to get access to the Black king.} *

