uch a foggy position will definitely enjoy the following lines. Maybe the force be with you!} 13. Rg1 Bf8 14. g4 Nxd5 15. g5 {Obviously, White needs to proceed in the most forceful fashion. Once the g or h file is open, it should all be over. The engine claims it's 'only' a big advantage for White. This generally means that Black still has defensive resources, which should not be underestimated. On the other hand, it's much easier to attack than to defend. Let's see how the game may proceed. Please keep in mind that all of this is original analysis, which never occurred in a game (at least not that I'm aware of).} d6 16. Rg3 {Covering the h3 square in order to avoid checks there (effectively freeing up the queen) . Let's not forget about the safety of our own king - one of Black's hopes is to give a check with the bishop on h3 while the rook is still on g1 and thus the king is stuck there. As long as we have the queen on h4 , it's fine. But what if we want to go with it somewhere?} Bg7 17. gxh6 Qxh4 18. Nxh4 Bh3+ {Not an easy move to be played. Black is lost if the g7 bishop falls.} 19. Rxh3 Bxh6 20. Rd1 Kf8 21. Nf5 Bg7 22. Rh7 {White still maintans a lot of pressure here but the game is obviously complex. Remember that opposite coloured bishop positions have drawish tendencies in the endgames. However, as long as the attack on the king is a possibility, the player who has the initiative, usually manages to get the advantage. Hence, White should play as actively as possible.} *

