1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bb4+ 8. Kf1 {Unfortunately, the right to castle is permanently lost. Well, at least until the next game. On a positive note, White will win the d pawn back. Typically, the rook from a1 will be moved to e1 .} O-O {Assuming that White doesn't even want to take the pawn in many instances, what's the point of protecting it? It is quite logical. I have to admit.} 9. Qxd4 h6 {For aesthetic reasons, let's make this our mainline.} 10. Bd3 {Improving the bishop while attacking another one.} Be7 {This move has never been played, but a fellow FM friend suggested this as a more natural move for Black when the 'beta testing' of this line took place.} 11. Bxh6 {Both spectacular and strong. White goes all in by sacrificing the bishop in return for a potentially powerful attack on the kingside, utilizing the g file as well as the a1 - h8 and b1 - h7 diagonals.} gxh6 12. Qh4 {White simply intends to capture the h6 pawn with almost checkmate on h7 . Defending this is very difficult in reality.} Re8 {A rather courageous attempt for Black. It leaves the h6 pawn unattended but prepares Bf8 - g7 defensive setup. With the best moves from both sides, the game will end up with a draw. I'm sorry. The good news is that Black will have to sweat to find all of those moves. The more likely outcome is an absolute chaos on the board. I'd love to tell you that you should simply trust your primal instinct and attack, mostly with g4 - g5 . For many of you, it will be specific enough. Those of you, who don't like being down a piece in such a foggy position will definitely enjoy the following lines. Maybe the force be with you!} 13. Rg1 Bf8 14. g4 d6 15. g5 Nd7 {This move is counterintuitive. Who would escape with the knight to queenside when the king is about to be slaughtered? Clearly a traitor as this move also blocks the bishop! Yet, it works tactically so what can we do.} 16. gxh6+ Kh8 {Transposes to 13... Bf8 14.g4 d6 .} 17. Qg3 (17. Qd4+ Ne5 18. Rg3 {Simply preventing} Bh3+ {ideas. Qf6 Re1 White introduced all of the pieces. The desired next move is Re4 intending Rf4 . Bf5 Black's strategy is simple: eliminate White's attacking pieces. Luckily, Black still has to solve the issue of open g -file. Things are not forced here, but let me show you a possible continuation: Bxf5 Qxf5 Re4 c6 dxc6 bxc6 Ng5 Qg6 Rf4 f5 Ne4 Qf7 Ng5 The engine claims the game should end up in a repetition, which is probably good news at this point. It looks like Black made some progress, so perhaps it's time to call it a day.}) 17... Nf6 {This logical move loses.} 18. Ng5 Qe7 19. Qf4 {Apparently, it's impossible to defend against Rg3 - e3 or Rf3 ideas. The biggest difficulty in such positions is related to the fact that Black needs to calculate all of this in advance and properly evaluate the position. Trust me, even strong titled playes may easily fail to do that.} *

