uch a foggy position will definitely enjoy the following lines. Maybe the force be with you!} 13. Rg1 Bf8 14. g4 d6 15. g5 Nd7 {This move is counterintuitive. Who would escape with the knight to queenside when the king is about to be slaughtered? Clearly a traitor as this move also blocks the bishop! Yet, it works tactically so what can we do.} 16. gxh6+ Kh8 {Transposes to 13... Bf8 14.g4 d6 .} 17. Qg3 (17. Qd4+ Ne5 18. Rg3 {Simply preventing} Bh3+ {ideas. Qf6 Re1 White introduced all of the pieces. The desired next move is Re4 intending Rf4 . Bf5 Black's strategy is simple: eliminate White's attacking pieces. Luckily, Black still has to solve the issue of open g -file. Things are not forced here, but let me show you a possible continuation: Bxf5 Qxf5 Re4 c6 dxc6 bxc6 Ng5 Qg6 Rf4 f5 Ne4 Qf7 Ng5 The engine claims the game should end up in a repetition, which is probably good news at this point. It looks like Black made some progress, so perhaps it's time to call it a day.}) 17... Bxh6 {On one hand, after this move, Black covers g8 square. On the other one, the h file is open now.} 18. Qh3 Qf6 19. Bg6 {Interception leading to a forced draw.} Qf4 (19... Kg7 {This is also possible and leads to draw after an insane defence by Black. Treat this line as a some kind of curiosity.} 20. Bxf7+ Kxf7 21. Qh5+ Ke7 22. Rg6 Bc1 {Apparently, this is the only move. I feel like I'm already showing too many weird lines in this chapter. Basically, Black is either going to counterattack with Rh8 (that's why Bf8 is bad) or take on b2 and sacrifice the queen for the rook.} 23. Qh7+ Kd8 24. Rxf6 Nxf6 25. Qh4 Bxb2 {The engine evaluates this position as equal but it still looks like a complete mess. I hate engines.}) (19... Qg7 20. Bf5 Qf6 {Black needs to repeat as Qf8 drops the knight on d7 . As long as the queen is on f6 , it keeps an eye on the f3 knight.}) 20. Ng5 {This is actually where Black is probably lost. There's just too many important objects hanging.} *

