uch a foggy position will definitely enjoy the following lines. Maybe the force be with you!} 13. Rg1 Bf8 14. g4 d6 15. g5 Nd7 {This move is counterintuitive. Who would escape with the knight to queenside when the king is about to be slaughtered? Clearly a traitor as this move also blocks the bishop! Yet, it works tactically so what can we do.} 16. gxh6+ Kh8 {Transposes to 13... Bf8 14.g4 d6 . You may try this move if you really wish to push for a win.} 17. Qf4 Qf6 {Surprisingly, the exchange of queens is not sufficient as White maintains annoying pressure with the wonderfully coordinated pieces. It's going to be awkward to protect f7 .} 18. Qxf6+ Nxf6 19. Ng5 Re7 20. Re1 Rd7 21. Re3 {Attempting to put the rook on f3 with even more pressure. All of this works due to Black's ridiculous placement of the pieces on queenside.} Bxh6 22. Bf5 {White's pressure will likely lead to material losses for Black. One important tactical idea is a simple transfer of the rook to h3 , which may even lead to checkmate - rooks on adjacent files should be enough in that regard.} *

