1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bb4+ 8. Kf1 {Unfortunately, the right to castle is permanently lost. Well, at least until the next game. On a positive note, White will win the d pawn back. Typically, the rook from a1 will be moved to e1 .} O-O {Assuming that White doesn't even want to take the pawn in many instances, what's the point of protecting it? It is quite logical. I have to admit.} 9. Qxd4 h6 {For aesthetic reasons, let's make this our mainline.} 10. Bd3 {Improving the bishop while attacking another one.} Be7 {This move has never been played, but a fellow FM friend suggested this as a more natural move for Black when the 'beta testing' of this line took place.} 11. Bxh6 {Both spectacular and strong. White goes all in by sacrificing the bishop in return for a potentially powerful attack on the kingside, utilizing the g file as well as the a1 - h8 and b1 - h7 diagonals.} gxh6 12. Qh4 {White simply intends to capture the h6 pawn with almost checkmate on h7 . Defending this is very difficult in reality.} Kg7 {The most obvious move.} 13. d6 {It seems that d5 - d6 is almost always at least a serious candidate move. As usual, the point is to disrupt Black's defensive coordination. Taking with the pawn will effectively mean that it will take ages to develop the c8 bishop. The drawback of the taking with tha piece is that it will not be as useful in defense as it could have been. In any case, d6 square will be blocked and so will the h3 - c8 diagonal be. It's important as Nd4 - f5 will often be a theme.} Bxd6 14. g4 {White intends to push g4 - g5 completely opening the crucial g file. Next, the rook will come to g1 and I already feel bad for Black.} Ng8 {Natural moves are just bad for Black. White is never going to trade the queens and the knight only makes an impression of protecting h6 .} 15. g5 {The engine already claims a completely winning position for White (something around +5 in the best scenario for Black. Thus, I will not show all of the possibilities that Black has at this point. The conversion part is on you, but I believe that the following sample line is a good illustration of White's cruel intentions.} Re8 16. gxh6+ {even worse is} Nxh6 17. Rg1+ Kf8 18. Qxh6+ Ke7 19. Re1+ Be5 20. Rxe5# {If you get this position in any of your games, you need to pay success fee to Chessable. True story.} *

