1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nb4 {One of the mainlines in the Belgrade Gambit. Black attempts to exchange our mighty knight on d5 without losing a tempo (which was the case after the immediate 5... Nxd5 ). In fact, the knight is attacked twice, which forces a reaction.} 6. Bc4 (6. Qxd4 $4 Nxc2+ {Say goodbye to your queen.}) 6... Nbxd5 7. exd5 {We have reached a very important branching point, so please make sure to study White's reactions properly.} Bb4+ 8. Kf1 {Unfortunately, the right to castle is permanently lost. Well, at least until the next game. On a positive note, White will win the d pawn back. Typically, the rook from a1 will be moved to e1 .} O-O {Assuming that White doesn't even want to take the pawn in many instances, what's the point of protecting it? It is quite logical. I have to admit.} 9. Qxd4 h6 {For aesthetic reasons, let's make this our mainline.} 10. Bd3 {Improving the bishop while attacking another one.} Qe7 {We reached a position, where White starts a shocking attack.} 11. Bxh6 {Unexpectedly, White can afford to sacrifice the bishop, as he will swiftly open the g file with an astonishing attack.} gxh6 12. g4 {Intending g4 - g5 and Rg1 - probably in that order.} Bc5 13. Qf4 Re8 14. Rg1 {White is about to push g4 - g5 . Black may survive this attack, but it will require a series of only moves. I guess if the opponent finds it, they deserve the draw.} Nxd5 15. Qf5 Qf6 16. Qxd5 d6 17. Rg3 {Protecting the rook and preparing g4 - g5 . I would be optimistic about White's chances.} *

