1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Be7 {A very logical move. Black focuses on quick development. The bishop's position is perhaps not impressive, but it does prevent Bg5 ideas.} 6. Bc4 {Other moves are certainly possible but this one appeals to me the most. What's more, Black is tempted to take the pawn on e4 , which leads to some spicy chess. A perfectly logical alternative for Black. It's a very a human reaction to run away from the centre, especially if one is surprised with the Belgrade Gambit!} O-O 7. O-O d6 8. Nxd4 {We probably need to recapture the pawn at this point. Apparently, Black is not in the mood for some exciting chess.} Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Nxd5 10. Bxd5 Bf6 {In my opinion, this is one of the best setups against the Belgrade Gambit - it's simple and deprives White of typical aggressive play. Most importantly, the knights are off the board, which generally means there is less chances for positional imbalances.} 11. Qd3 {We saw a similar type of a position above. In the future, White will probably play c2 - c3 to neutralize the bishop on f6 and prepare a Bd5 - b3 - c2 regrouping should White decide to create a battery along the b1 - h7 diagonal.} *

