1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Be7 {A very logical move. Black focuses on quick development. The bishop's position is perhaps not impressive, but it does prevent Bg5 ideas.} 6. Bc4 {Other moves are certainly possible but this one appeals to me the most. What's more, Black is tempted to take the pawn on e4 , which leads to some spicy chess. A perfectly logical alternative for Black. It's a very a human reaction to run away from the centre, especially if one is surprised with the Belgrade Gambit!} O-O 7. O-O Nxd5 8. exd5 {An important move, White voluntarily restricts the bishop by recapturing with the pawn. On the other hand, the black knight has to move somewhere and it's not clear where it should go. On top of that, the d4 pawn will not be protected anymore. Whether we should capture it or not, it's a different story.} Nb8 {It's always weirdly satisfying when the opponent needs to retreat a piece to its original position.} 9. Nxd4 d6 10. a4 {Expanding on the queenside and possibly preparing Ra3 in order to transfer the rook to the kingside.} Nd7 11. a5 {Intending to push the pawn to a6 to soften Black pawn formation and get access to c6 square.} Ne5 12. Be2 Bf6 13. Be3 {White enjoys an edge thanks to the more active pieces and more space.} *

