1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Be7 {A very logical move. Black focuses on quick development. The bishop's position is perhaps not impressive, but it does prevent Bg5 ideas.} 6. Bc4 {Other moves are certainly possible but this one appeals to me the most. What's more, Black is tempted to take the pawn on e4 , which leads to some spicy chess. A perfectly logical alternative for Black. It's a very a human reaction to run away from the centre, especially if one is surprised with the Belgrade Gambit!} O-O 7. O-O Nxd5 8. exd5 {An important move, White voluntarily restricts the bishop by recapturing with the pawn. On the other hand, the black knight has to move somewhere and it's not clear where it should go. On top of that, the d4 pawn will not be protected anymore. Whether we should capture it or not, it's a different story.} Na5 9. Bd3 {In order to understand Black's main problem, it's worth looking at what would happen if White could make another move.} (9. Z0 {b4} Bb4 {Bxh7+ the classic bishop sacrifice is available and White has a finishing attack. Kxh7} 10. Ng5 {Kg8 Qh5+- Black will soon get checkmated or lose the queen.}) 9... c5 {Long story short: Black should not allow b2 - b4 as this deflects the bishop from e7 . In turn, the bishop on e7 prevents Bxh7 ideas as it covers the critical g5 square.} 10. d6 {You've seen this move before. The purpose is twofold: lure the bishop into taking on d6 to enable Bxh7 sacrifice and freeze the d7 pawn.} Bf6 11. b4 {It's pivotal to prevent c5 - c4 , even at the cost of a pawn.} (11. Re1 {was played in the all-Russian duel 0-1 Postny, E (2600)-Oparin, G (2652) lichess.org INT 2020 but the mainline is far more convincing.}) 11... cxb4 12. h4 {It's good we're in a computer era as finding such 2 moves in a row would not be easy. The purpose of b2 - b4 was the demolishion of Black's pawn structure so that c5 - c4 harassing our bishop was never an option. You can probably guess the aim of h2 - h4 : controlling g5 more efficiently so that one of our minor pieces could go there.} h6 13. Ng5 {Yet another insane piece sacrifice. Such ideas normally work with the rook on h1 instead of f1 . Thanks to Black's bad piece coordination and rather slow development on queenside, this idea may actually work. Capturing the knight seems a bit too greedy.} hxg5 14. hxg5 Bxg5 15. Qh5 {Black is busted here.} Bh6 16. Bxh6 gxh6 17. Qxh6 {Threatening mate on h7 .} Re8 {It doesn't help Black in view of the checkmate attack. Wow, it even rhymes!} 18. Qh7+ Kf8 19. Qh8# *

