1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Be7 {A very logical move. Black focuses on quick development. The bishop's position is perhaps not impressive, but it does prevent Bg5 ideas.} 6. Bc4 {Other moves are certainly possible but this one appeals to me the most. What's more, Black is tempted to take the pawn on e4 , which leads to some spicy chess.} d6 {Another solid try for Black.} 7. Nxd4 {White wins the pawn back but in return Black manages to simplify the game and get a well-coordinated army.} Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Nxd5 9. Bxd5 O-O 10. O-O Bf6 {This is the point. Thanks to the active bishop on the long diagonal, Black is relatively safe. The space advantage is not relevant anymore as there is much less pieces on the board.} 11. Qd3 {We're preparing a little rearrangement of our forces. Usually this means c2 - c3 to neutralize Black's bishop, rerouting the bishop to c2 via b3 and either f2 - f4 playing for kingside pawn majority or simply Bf4 . Black has multiple options and I don't think it's particularly important to learn them by heart. Just go through the sample lines to get a good indication of the possible ideas for both sides. CLICKABLE} Re8 12. Rb1 {Normally I would suggest playing c2 - c3 but another idea is to play b4 - b5 and fix Black's pawn structure, especially the b7 pawn.} a5 {Preventing b2 - b4 .} 13. a4 Qe7 14. Bf4 Be5 15. Bd2 {Intending f4 - f5 in order to open the f file and attack the f7 pawn.} c6 16. Bb3 Be6 {Black should definitely exchange the ligh-squared bishop. This is another argument for transfering the bishop to c2 .} 17. Bxe6 Qxe6 18. f4 Bf6 19. Rfe1 {The game is balanced but I feel that White has somewhat easier moves. The pawns on a5 and d6 are obvious targets and White has a slightly better pawn structure. The next moves may include: b3 and Rad1 . In the meantime, Black will probably play b6 , Rad8 and possibly look for d6 - d5 break.} *

