1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Be7 {A very logical move. Black focuses on quick development. The bishop's position is perhaps not impressive, but it does prevent Bg5 ideas.} 6. Bc4 {Other moves are certainly possible but this one appeals to me the most. What's more, Black is tempted to take the pawn on e4 , which leads to some spicy chess.} Nxe4 7. O-O {For a split second Black has coordination issues. The knight on e4 as well as the king on e8 mean a chance for creating tactical motifs along the e file. Black needs to castle as quickly as possible and retreat the knight. In the meantime, White will attempt to develop a powerful initative.} O-O 8. Re1 {Simple and strong, White needs to put immediate pressure on the e file.} Nf6 9. Nxe7+ Nxe7 10. Qxd4 {White is down a pawn for a bishop pair in an open position. This should be enough to claim full compensation.} d5 11. Bd3 {Honestly, there is not more than equality for White now, especially after the strong 11... Ng6 move. In other lines, White still has a few aces up the sleeve.} Bf5 {Black could try this logical move. After all, if he manages to exchange the bishops, we will just be left down a pawn.} 12. Rxe7 {This came out of nowhere! Thanks to the presented tactical trick, White manages to hold the balance.} Bxd3 13. Qe5 {It's fair to say that White has compensation for the pawn due to the active queen and rook. In order to properly assess such a position, it's important to understand that there are opposite-coloured bishops on the board. Long story short: the player who manages to seize the initiative, has the better chances. Consequently, White needs to play aggressively and put pressure on Black. Like anything changed, I know, I know.. . In case such a summary is enough for you, feel free to stop studying the following sample lines as they're main objective is to present how the game may proceed.} ({Bxc2 In this position, White has 2 interesting, equivalent options.   A) Qxc7⇆ White simply takes the pawn back, maintaining the pressure along the 7th rank. Many moves could be tried here by Black as the game is not so forcing anymore. White will likely win another pawn. The next moves should involve developing the bishop and possibly putting a minor piece on d4 with good prospects.   B)} 13. Bg5 {The difference between the strategy of both players couldn't be more evident. White seeks compensation for the missing pawns by playing as actively as possible and putting pressure on Black's kingside.} Ng4 ({(} 13... Be4 {This is engine's suggestion for Black.} 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Qxf6 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Qd6 {A unique situation has arisen on the g file, but it seems that neither of the players will manage to benefit from the opponent's exposed king. Black will liquidate to a rook endgame.} 17. Qxd6 cxd6 18. Rd1 {White will win a pawn back. As they say, all rook endgames are drawish but White enjoys the better side of the equality thanks to the more active rooks).}) {Qg3⩲ f6} 14. Rxc7 {White already regained a pawn and attacks 2 minor pieces at the same time. The position remains complex but White's chances are much better mainly due to his active pieces.}) ({Be4 A natural retreat, which also centralized the bishop and attacks the knight, threatening to create doubled f pawns in White's camp. Qxc7 Bxf3 gxf3= The position is balanced, despite obvious imbalances. White has a more active queen and a rook, but there is the other rook in the corner and an unemployed bishop (he preferred to say he's between the jobs). When activated, the bishop should become a more influential piece than the knight considering the open character of the position. Further, White has a compromised kingside pawn structure but Black has an isolani. The king safety should not be an issue once the queens are exchanged. I would expect White to play} 13. Be3 {or Bg5 , trade the queens and develop the other rook to d1 with good chances for a success.}) *

