1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Be7 {A very logical move. Black focuses on quick development. The bishop's position is perhaps not impressive, but it does prevent Bg5 ideas.} 6. Bc4 {Other moves are certainly possible but this one appeals to me the most. What's more, Black is tempted to take the pawn on e4 , which leads to some spicy chess.} Nxe4 7. O-O {For a split second Black has coordination issues. The knight on e4 as well as the king on e8 mean a chance for creating tactical motifs along the e file. Black needs to castle as quickly as possible and retreat the knight. In the meantime, White will attempt to develop a powerful initative.} O-O 8. Re1 {Simple and strong, White needs to put immediate pressure on the e file.} Nf6 9. Nxe7+ Nxe7 10. Qxd4 {White is down a pawn for a bishop pair in an open position. This should be enough to claim full compensation.} d5 11. Bd3 {Honestly, there is not more than equality for White now, especially after the strong 11... Ng6 move. In other lines, White still has a few aces up the sleeve.} Ng6 12. Bg5 h6 {In order to get clear equality, White should probably liquidate to an endgame.} 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Qxf6 gxf6 15. Bxg6 fxg6 16. Re7 {The activity of the rook should secure equality.} ({c5 Rd1 Rd8 Rc7 b6 Re1 Bf5} 16. Re7 {White has enough activity for the missing pawn.}) *

