1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Bc5 {It's a very important line. To my surprise, it is not employed frequently. Black provokes 6.Bg5 with a pin. The problem is that Black will then retreat to e7 with the bishop and White pretty much has to go back to f4 . As a result, we have a 5... Be7 6.Bf4 line with both sides losing a tempo. However, I never intended to recommend 6. Bf4 against the Be7 system. Therefore, my main remedy against Bc5 system will be a bit different.} 6. Bf4 d6 7. Bg5 {The bishop keeps on dancing! You shouldn't make multiple moves in the opening with the same piece unless the author of the course tells you to do so. Here, you have my blessing to create the pin along the h4 - d8 diagonal. As usual, this means paralysing Black's forces to a degree. It will be impossible to take on e4 or d5 , which is already something to cherish.} Ne5 {This is engine's suggestion. It leads to a weird position but I couldn't find anything better despite spending hours analyzing White's possibilities. How can you fight the engine after all?!} 8. b4 {The main aim of this move is to force the Black bishop back to b6 . Any other move would soon allow a powerful idea: c6 followed by Qb6 with a dangerous battery potentially hitting f2 . Trust me, it's better to avoid it.} Nxd5 {This sacrifice should not be taken lightly.} 9. Bxd8 Bxb4+ 10. Nd2 Nc3 11. Qh5 Bg4 12. Qh4 {Luckily, the queen doesn't get trapped.} Rxd8 13. a3 Ba5 14. Bd3 {The dust settled and we have a strange position on the board. White enjoys a material advantage but Black has more pieces, more pawns and better coordination. I feel that moves like f3 and Nb3 should be a good starting point to a good game for White but all results are still possible.} *

