1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Bc5 {It's a very important line. To my surprise, it is not employed frequently. Black provokes 6.Bg5 with a pin. The problem is that Black will then retreat to e7 with the bishop and White pretty much has to go back to f4 . As a result, we have a 5... Be7 6.Bf4 line with both sides losing a tempo. However, I never intended to recommend 6. Bf4 against the Be7 system. Therefore, my main remedy against Bc5 system will be a bit different.} 6. Bf4 d6 7. Bg5 {The bishop keeps on dancing! You shouldn't make multiple moves in the opening with the same piece unless the author of the course tells you to do so. Here, you have my blessing to create the pin along the h4 - d8 diagonal. As usual, this means paralysing Black's forces to a degree. It will be impossible to take on e4 or d5 , which is already something to cherish.} Be6 8. Bb5 {Thanks to the pin along a4 - e8 diagonal, White threatens to win the d pawn.} Bxd5 9. exd5 {This gives White an easy way to an advantage. The following sequence is pretty much forcing.} a6 {Otherwise, Black loses a piece.} 10. dxc6 axb5 11. cxb7 Rb8 12. Qd3 Rxb7 13. O-O-O {Once the king is no longer on e1 , White threatens Bxf6 followed by Qe4 winning a rook.} O-O 14. Nxd4 {White has the better chances, mainly due to better piece coordination and the annoying pin along the h4 - d8 diagonal. Naturally, White should attack on kingside.} *

