1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Bc5 {It's a very important line. To my surprise, it is not employed frequently. Black provokes 6.Bg5 with a pin. The problem is that Black will then retreat to e7 with the bishop and White pretty much has to go back to f4 . As a result, we have a 5... Be7 6.Bf4 line with both sides losing a tempo. However, I never intended to recommend 6. Bf4 against the Be7 system. Therefore, my main remedy against Bc5 system will be a bit different.} 6. Bf4 O-O {A very important move! Black does not need to protect the c7 pawn. In fact, taking it would be reckless for White due worse development and the king stuck in the centre. Suddenly, the tables have turned!} 7. Bd3 Nxd5 8. exd5 Ne7 {It seems illogical. If it's possible to introduce the rook into the game, why not doing it before moving the knight. Once more, White gets a chance to attack in style.} 9. Bxh7+ Kh8 {Probably the best as now Black threatens g7 - g6 .} 10. Be4 f5 11. Bd3 Nxd5 12. Bg5 Qe8+ 13. Kf1 {The game is dynamically balanced, but I prefer White's attacking potential on kingside with ideas like Nh4 , Bc4 or simple caveman attack: h4 - h5 - h6 .} *

