1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Bc5 {It's a very important line. To my surprise, it is not employed frequently. Black provokes 6.Bg5 with a pin. The problem is that Black will then retreat to e7 with the bishop and White pretty much has to go back to f4 . As a result, we have a 5... Be7 6.Bf4 line with both sides losing a tempo. However, I never intended to recommend 6. Bf4 against the Be7 system. Therefore, my main remedy against Bc5 system will be a bit different.} 6. Bf4 O-O {A very important move! Black does not need to protect the c7 pawn. In fact, taking it would be reckless for White due worse development and the king stuck in the centre. Suddenly, the tables have turned!} 7. Bd3 Nxd5 8. exd5 Qe7+ 9. Kd2 {If there's a competition for the biggest number of spectacular moves in an opening course, I'd like to participate! Ok, but what's going on this time? Apparently, the White king will not be safe on f1 after our usual sacrifice on h7 . Further, Kd2 facilitates the connection of the rooks, which will prove to be the key difference.} (9. Kf1 $2 Nb4 10. Bxh7+ Kxh7 11. Ng5+ Kg6 12. Qg4 f5 13. Qg3 b6 {It may look like White still has some attacking chances using h4 - h5 battering ram but the engine disagrees. After Ba6 Black gets enough counterplay according to the engine. In fact, it claims Black is winning already.} 14. Re1 $4 {Blunders the rook.} Ba6+ {White is lost as the rook is only protected by the king, which is checked.}) 9... Nb4 10. Bxh7+ Kh8 {Taking the bishop will be traumatizing.} 11. Re1 Qf6 12. Bg5 Qd6 13. Bf5 {The bishop escaped but Black won the d5 pawn finally.} Nxd5 14. a3 {White prevents any Bb4 tricks. The position remains complex but White has more attacking options, such as: Re4 - Rh4 , Nh4 followed by Qh5 or even Ne5 . The king on d2 is relatively safe. Enjoy!} *

