1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Bc5 {It's a very important line. To my surprise, it is not employed frequently. Black provokes 6.Bg5 with a pin. The problem is that Black will then retreat to e7 with the bishop and White pretty much has to go back to f4 . As a result, we have a 5... Be7 6.Bf4 line with both sides losing a tempo. However, I never intended to recommend 6. Bf4 against the Be7 system. Therefore, my main remedy against Bc5 system will be a bit different.} 6. Bf4 O-O {A very important move! Black does not need to protect the c7 pawn. In fact, taking it would be reckless for White due worse development and the king stuck in the centre. Suddenly, the tables have turned!} 7. Bd3 Nxd5 8. exd5 Qe7+ 9. Kd2 {If there's a competition for the biggest number of spectacular moves in an opening course, I'd like to participate! Ok, but what's going on this time? Apparently, the White king will not be safe on f1 after our usual sacrifice on h7 . Further, Kd2 facilitates the connection of the rooks, which will prove to be the key difference.} (9. Kf1 $2 Nb4 10. Bxh7+ Kxh7 11. Ng5+ Kg6 12. Qg4 f5 13. Qg3 b6 {It may look like White still has some attacking chances using h4 - h5 battering ram but the engine disagrees. After Ba6 Black gets enough counterplay according to the engine. In fact, it claims Black is winning already.} 14. Re1 $4 {Blunders the rook.} Ba6+ {White is lost as the rook is only protected by the king, which is checked.}) 9... Nb4 10. Bxh7+ Kh8 {Taking the bishop will be traumatizing.} 11. Re1 Qf6 12. Bg5 Qb6 {This is a critical position in this line. White has multiple options and all of them lead to advanterous or even bizarre play. I chose 2 most rational ones but feel free to spend some extra time on you own investigating moves like: 13. Re4 or 13.Be4. ALTERNATIVE} 13. Bf5 Nxd5 14. Re5 {The purpose of this move is obviously to hit the knight and avoid any Bb4 nonsense.} Nf6 15. Nh4 {White threatens to take on f6 and then play Qh5 practically winning.} Kg8 {Virtually forced. Now the engine suggests the wild} 16. Rxc5 Qxc5 17. Bxf6 Qa5+ 18. c3 (18. Kc1 $2 {is not advisable as it allows counterplay.} Re8 {There's no good way to stop Re1 .}) 18... Qb6 {Not an easy idea to be found in advance, not to mention the evaluation.} 19. Qh5 Qxb2+ 20. Bc2 Qxc3+ 21. Kd1 Qxa1+ 22. Kd2 Qc3+ 23. Kd1 {Draw. If the opponent finds all of those moves, just congratulate them on an exceptionally good game.} *

