1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Bc5 {It's a very important line. To my surprise, it is not employed frequently. Black provokes 6.Bg5 with a pin. The problem is that Black will then retreat to e7 with the bishop and White pretty much has to go back to f4 . As a result, we have a 5... Be7 6.Bf4 line with both sides losing a tempo. However, I never intended to recommend 6. Bf4 against the Be7 system. Therefore, my main remedy against Bc5 system will be a bit different.} 6. Bf4 O-O {A very important move! Black does not need to protect the c7 pawn. In fact, taking it would be reckless for White due worse development and the king stuck in the centre. Suddenly, the tables have turned!} 7. Bd3 Nxd5 8. exd5 Re8+ {Definitely the best continuation as White will be looking for sacrifices on h7 anyway.} 9. Kf1 {It's worth remembering those subtle differences. On 8... Qe7 we play 9.Kd2 and on 8... Re8 , play 9.Kf1.} Ne7 10. d6 {Clever as usual! Black is unable to play d7 - d6 thus introducing the bishop into play.} ({Let me show you why the immediate Bxh7 doesn't work:} 10. Bxh7+ $4 Kxh7 11. Ng5+ Kg8 12. Qh5 Ng6 13. Qh7+ Kf8 {Now it's clear why the Re8 move was useful.}) (10. Ng5 $2 {this also leads to nothing.} Ng6 11. Qh5 h6 12. h4 Qf6 {Black is not forced to take on g5 . The queen threatens to win the bishop on f4 .} 13. Bg3 d6 {White's attack is out of steam. Black is about to develop the bishop from c8 with a batter game.}) 10... cxd6 11. Ng5 Ng6 12. Qh5 Nxf4 {Black gets mated now.} 13. Bxh7+ Kf8 14. Qxf7# *

