1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Bc5 {It's a very important line. To my surprise, it is not employed frequently. Black provokes 6.Bg5 with a pin. The problem is that Black will then retreat to e7 with the bishop and White pretty much has to go back to f4 . As a result, we have a 5... Be7 6.Bf4 line with both sides losing a tempo. However, I never intended to recommend 6. Bf4 against the Be7 system. Therefore, my main remedy against Bc5 system will be a bit different.} 6. Bf4 O-O {A very important move! Black does not need to protect the c7 pawn. In fact, taking it would be reckless for White due worse development and the king stuck in the centre. Suddenly, the tables have turned!} 7. Bd3 Nxd5 8. exd5 Re8+ {Definitely the best continuation as White will be looking for sacrifices on h7 anyway.} 9. Kf1 {It's worth remembering those subtle differences. On 8... Qe7 we play 9.Kd2 and on 8... Re8 , play 9.Kf1.} Ne7 10. d6 {Clever as usual! Black is unable to play d7 - d6 thus introducing the bishop into play.} ({Let me show you why the immediate Bxh7 doesn't work:} 10. Bxh7+ $4 Kxh7 11. Ng5+ Kg8 12. Qh5 Ng6 13. Qh7+ Kf8 {Now it's clear why the Re8 move was useful.}) (10. Ng5 $2 {this also leads to nothing.} Ng6 11. Qh5 h6 12. h4 Qf6 {Black is not forced to take on g5 . The queen threatens to win the bishop on f4 .} 13. Bg3 d6 {White's attack is out of steam. Black is about to develop the bishop from c8 with a batter game.}) 10... Ng6 {The strongest of all of Black's options but who allows dxc7 ?!} 11. dxc7 Qe7 12. Bg3 d6 {Finally Black is about to include the bishop in the game.} 13. h4 Ne5 14. h5 {Preparing h5 - h6 and Rh4 in order to control valuable squares on the 4th rank and attack the d pawn.} h6 15. Rh4 Bg4 16. Bb5 Rec8 17. Qe2 Rxc7 18. Re1 {The engine has a slight preference for Black but in human terms this looks equal. White's next move should be Qe4 and then possible the bishop should retreat to d3 .} *

