1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Bc5 {It's a very important line. To my surprise, it is not employed frequently. Black provokes 6.Bg5 with a pin. The problem is that Black will then retreat to e7 with the bishop and White pretty much has to go back to f4 . As a result, we have a 5... Be7 6.Bf4 line with both sides losing a tempo. However, I never intended to recommend 6. Bf4 against the Be7 system. Therefore, my main remedy against Bc5 system will be a bit different.} 6. Bg5 {I will show you a different direction, which you may want to test occasionally. It may be a good way to dry the game if this is what you wish to happen.} Be7 7. Bxf6 {Considering the sharpness of the line I will propose, it's good to have a backup plan. It leads to equality, but this may be a good outcome on certain days.} (7. Bf4 d6 {It's well-known that Black has nothing to worry about in this line.}) 7... Bxf6 8. Bb5 {White simply intends to take on c6 , take on f6 and ultimately grab the d4 pawn with a superior pawn structure.} O-O 9. O-O Re8 10. Nxf6+ Qxf6 11. Re1 {Now that the e4 pawn is protected, White is ready to capture on c6 and d4 . In case the queens get exchanged, White may still hope to squeeze more than a draw thanks to the better pawn structure. However, let's remember that Black has a bishop for a knight in an open position so all results are still possible.} *

