1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Bc5 {It's a very important line. To my surprise, it is not employed frequently. Black provokes 6.Bg5 with a pin. The problem is that Black will then retreat to e7 with the bishop and White pretty much has to go back to f4 . As a result, we have a 5... Be7 6.Bf4 line with both sides losing a tempo. However, I never intended to recommend 6. Bf4 against the Be7 system. Therefore, my main remedy against Bc5 system will be a bit different.} 6. Bg5 {I will show you a different direction, which you may want to test occasionally. It may be a good way to dry the game if this is what you wish to happen.} Be7 7. Bxf6 {Considering the sharpness of the line I will propose, it's good to have a backup plan. It leads to equality, but this may be a good outcome on certain days.} (7. Bf4 d6 {It's well-known that Black has nothing to worry about in this line.}) 7... Bxf6 8. Bb5 {White simply intends to take on c6 , take on f6 and ultimately grab the d4 pawn with a superior pawn structure.} O-O 9. O-O a6 10. Bxc6 dxc6 11. Nxf6+ Qxf6 12. Qxd4 Qxd4 13. Nxd4 {The pawn structure may remind you of the Berlin Defense in Ruy Lopez. There is less pieces on the board, which should favor White. On the other hand, Black has the bishop versus knight advantage in an open position. I like White's practical chances in such an endgame but I can imagine it's not to everyone's taste. We're following a high profile game of two strong GMs. Let's see how they approached the given task:} ({c5 Ne2 f5 Nc3 fxe4 Nxe4 b6} 13. Rfe1 Bf5 14. Re2 {White never got anything realistic here 1/2 Bernadskiy, V (2594)-Predke, A (2632) Riga 2019.}) *

