{Let's take a look at one of the most spectacular wins in the Belgrade Gambit I managed to find in my database. I am certain that this game insipred many generations to try this opening.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 {Let the party begin!} Nxe4 {Out of all of Black's possibilities, this seems to be the most testing one. After all, White is down 2 pawns after only 5 moves!} 6. Qe2 {The legendary Spanish / Swedish GM Juan Bellon tried this straight-forward move on numerous occasions.} (6. Bd3 $5 {This is my suggestion for this course. I prefer to develop the entire kingside and castle short as quickly as possible. I believe that such a healthy approach currently gives White the best practical chances.}) 6... f5 {Only this move doesn't lose the knight. Its obvious drawback is that it exposes the Black king} 7. Bf4 ({It's important not to play} 7. Nd2 d3 $1 {A common resource for Black when the queen is on e2 .} 8. Qxd3 ({(} 8. cxd3 Nd4 $1 {All of the sudden, Black takes over the initiative.} 9. Qd1 {The only move as Nc2 with a fork was on the agenda.} Nf6 10. Nc3 Bc5 {Black is simply better here.)}) 8... Nb4 9. Nxb4 Bxb4 10. c3 Bc5 11. Nxe4 Qe7 {This gives Black the better chances.}) (7. Ng5 {According to the analysts, this is a much stronger continuation. Let's remember that the stem game was played before the computer era. Hence, the human 7.Bf4 was a very serious try.}) 7... d6 ({Another interesting line is} 7... Bd6 8. Bxd6 cxd6 9. b4 ({(} 9. O-O-O Qa5 {Black fights back with the active queen. The position is dynamically balanced.)}) 9... O-O 10. Qc4 Kh8 11. Be2 b5 {The purpose of this move becomes evident when White takes on b5 .} 12. Qd3 ({(} 12. Qxb5 a5 {Black is about to play Ba6 with a lethal effect as White suffers from bad piece coordination.)}) 12... Nc3 ({(Better was} 12... a5 13. O-O Nxb4 14. Nxb4 axb4 {Black's pawn structure is certainly uncommon but it's still a 2 pawn advantage.)}) 13. Nxc3 dxc3 ({(Better was} 13... Nxb4 14. Qd2 dxc3 15. Qxc3 Nd5 {with a convincing advantage - two pawns up and a safer king is a lot.)}) 14. O-O Qf6 15. Rfd1 Re8 {The game went on and eventually Black failed to convert his advantage 1/2 (48) Piskur,M (2234) -Pavasovic,D (2515) Ljubljana 2001}) 8. O-O-O Ne5 {This is just bad. White invites more friends to the party and the assault on the Black king is inevitable.} (8... Ne7 $1 {This strange-looking move secures Black's advantage and essentially refutes the 6.Qe2 line. The main purpose is to exchange the powerful knight on d5 and consolidate fast. Another benefit is the possibility of playing c7 - c5 in some lines.} 9. Nxe7 ({(} 9. Nxd4 $2 {This invites too many exchanges and Black gets a good position by force.} Nxd5 10. Nxf5 {A few more explosions in the centre before the game settles.} Bxf5 11. Rxd5 Qf6 12. f3 Be7 13. fxe4 Be6 {Black has a positional advantage due to better development and slightly better pawn structure.}) 9... Bxe7 10. g4 ({(} 10. Nxd4 O-O 11. f3 Nc5 12. h4 Bf6 {It looks like a convincing way to neutralize White's aggression. I don't believe White has any compensation for the pawn.} 13. Kb1 Bd7 14. Bg5 {White does everything in his power to open the position and the game remains complex. However, objectively Black just enjoys a pawn advantage.} Kh8 15. Qc4 a5 16. Bd3 a4 17. f4 c6 {Black went on to winning in Bellon Lopez,J-Sznapik,A/ Stockholm 1969.}) 10... c5 {Black fortifies the critical d4 pawn and thus ensures a plus in this sharp position. Black is about to finalize the development, which ends White's dream about a success in the Belgrade Gambit.} 11. Bh3 fxg4 12. Qxe4 d5 $1 {Without panicking Black improves his pawn formation.} 13. Qe5 O-O {-+ Black's material advantage was decisive in Hartoch,R (2405)-Timman,J (2585) Leeuwarden 1978}) 9. Rxd4 c6 10. Nxe5 {It turns out that this is just ubearable for Black.} dxe5 (10... cxd5 {White will win the game by dominating on light squares.} 11. Qh5+ g6 12. Bb5+ Ke7 13. Nxg6+ {This leads to huge material gains.}) 11. Rxe4 {White takes advantage of Black's exposed king. Please pay attention to White's tremendous lead in development!} Bd6 (11... cxd5 12. Rxe5+ Kf7 13. Qf3 {The material balance is the only good piece of information for Black. He will not have time catch up in development and find safety for the king.} Be6 14. Bd3 g6 15. Rhe1 {The pressure created by logical moves is simply overwhelming.}) (11... Qxd5 12. Rxe5+ {Obviously, this just loses the queen.}) 12. Rxe5+ {White breaks through irrespective of the costs!} Kf7 (12... Bxe5 13. Qxe5+ Kf7 14. Nc7 {threatening both Nxa8 and Bc4 with further problems} Rb8 15. Bc4+ Kg6 16. h4 h5 17. Rh3 {When the last piece joins the action, it typically means it is over.}) 13. Nc7 {What a display of tactical vision!!!} Qxc7 (13... Bxc7 14. Qh5+ Kf8 ({(} 14... g6 15. Bc4+ Be6 16. Bxe6+ Ke8 17. Qe2 {Black will be crushed any moment.)}) 15. Bc4 Qd7 16. Rd1 {Black is helpless against White's entire army.}) 14. Qh5+ {At this point Black resigned. I have to admit, White's win was certainly impressive. However, as presented by GM Timman, Black is absolutely fine if he chooses the 8... Ne7 setup. As such, I can't recommend GM Bellon's approach to Belgrade Gambit.} ({Black resigned due to the following line} 14. Qh5+ g6 15. Bc4+ Kf6 16. Bg5+ Kxe5 17. Qe2+ Kd4 18. c3+ Kc5 19. Be3# {Was probably expected by Black.}) *

