{I chose to demonstrate this game for purely informative purposes. It shows how the innocent-looking types of positions with seemingly no action on the board may be poisonous for White. Go through the game, read the annotations and never do this at home! Instead follow my recommendations in the theoretical section.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Be7 6. Nxd4 {Slap on the wrist! Recapturing the pawn may be tempting but it is positionally incorrect. Now Black is allowed to exchange too many pieces and our space advantage is no longer an important factor. GM Tseshkovsky presents how to handle such a position properly with Black.} (6. Bc4 {This is my recommendation.}) 6... Nxd5 7. exd5 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 O-O 9. Be2 Bf6 {All of the sudden, Black starts attacking the White pieces and asks unpleasant questions. Where will the queen go? How will you develop the bishop from c1 while protecting b2 ? Are you prepared for the pin along the e file? An amateur can find those moves for Black.} 10. Qd3 d6 11. c3 (11. O-O {Escaping from the centre was perhaps slightly more precise. However, the character of the position remains the same. Black has simple moves and White needs to create some out of nothing to hope for an edge.} Re8 {The position is dull and I don't really see how White could seize initiative here.}) 11... Re8 12. Be3 {Clearly, GM Savchenko did not sense the danger.} ({Better was} 12. O-O {Again, safety first.}) 12... Bg5 {Black virtually forces either an unfavourable exchange of the bishops leading to Black's initiative or White compromising his pawn structure.} 13. f4 (13. Bxg5 Qxg5 14. O-O Bf5 15. Qd1 Be4 16. Bf3 {White manages to hold the equality but it is certainly not a pleasant type of a position as Black has the better pieces, control of the e file and realistic chances to attack d5 pawn.}) 13... Bh6 (13... Bf5 $5 {Black had a cunning idea at his disposal. A sample line goes:} 14. Qxf5 Rxe3 15. fxg5 Qe7 16. Qf2 Re8 {Kids, this is why it is important to occupy an open file with your major pieces! Black is much better if not technically winning already.}) 14. Kd2 Qf6 15. Qd4 Qg6 {Black maintains to put pressure on the kingside by keeping the queens on the board.} 16. Bf3 Bg4 {I adore Black's play for its simplicity. Such moves are not difficult if you understand the game and the requirements of the position. Black simply wants to get access to e4 square by exchanging the bishops.} 17. Bxg4 Qxg4 18. g3 Re7 19. Rae1 Rae8 20. Qxa7 {On one hand this is greedy but on the other one, at least White knew what he was suffering for: a pawn is a pawn.} c5 {This in fact gives White a second life.} ({Much better was} 20... Qf3 21. Qd4 Qg2+ 22. Bf2 Re4 23. Kc1 g5 {with nagging pressure} ({Obviously not} 23... Rxd4 $4 24. Rxe8# {A classic back rank checkmate will never be out of fashion.})) 21. dxc6 bxc6 22. Bf2 {This is a decisive mistake as Black penetrates White's position with the major pieces.} (22. Qd4 $5 {White could still hold this position and even hope for more in long run.}) 22... Re2+ 23. Rxe2 Rxe2+ 24. Kc1 g5 {The strength of this move probably surprised young Boris Savchenko.} 25. Rd1 gxf4 26. Qb8+ Bf8 27. Ba7 f3 {White resigned due to lack of sufficient defensive resources against moves like Qe4 / Qf5 / Qg6 threatening Qc2 checkmate or f2 preparing promotion. I bet White regretted playing 6.Nxd4 for the majority of this game.} *

