{From the theoretical perspective, this game itself is not particularly important but combined with corresponding analysis clearly presents the drawback of the most aggressive setup White has at his disposal after 6.Qe2 f5 . As far as I can tell, this line is pretty much refuted.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxe4 6. Qe2 f5 7. Ng5 {Understandably, for many years, this has been considered the most promising move for White. After all, it directly hits the knight on e4 , threatening to regain the material and start the assault along the open e file. Unless Black is prepared or has good calculation skills, this position might already be problematic. In fact, Black is forced to enter a very dynamic move sequence. Unfortunately, said sequence leads to nothing good for White.} d3 {Two exclamation marks are deserved in my opinion. One for the strength of this move, one for its importance. Basically, Black starts a counterattack instead of defending passively.} 8. cxd3 (8. Qxd3 {Without the pin along the e file, White's attack is too slow.} Nb4 9. Nxb4 Bxb4+ 10. c3 Bd6 11. Nxe4 Qe7 {Black is doing fine here. The knight will be regained by Black with a safer king and possibly a better pawn structure.}) 8... Nd4 {All of the sudden, Black's knights become invincible.} 9. Qh5+ (9. Nxe4 $4 {This interesting attempt just doesn't work tactically.} Nxe2 10. Bg5 Nf4 $3 11. Nxf4 ({(} 11. Bxd8 Nxd5 {White is unable to protect both hanging minor pieces.)}) 11... Be7 {Since e7 square is only attacked once by White, Black can save his queen by developing the bishop.}) 9... g6 10. Qh4 c6 {A very important move. Certain alternatives were tried, especially Nc2 but it is simply a bit too optimistic.} (10... Nc2+ 11. Kd1 Nxa1 12. dxe4 {Despite the material deficit and a rather 'unique' position of his king, White has a huge advantage due to the activity of his pieces. The knight on a1 might also be trapped later on.}) 11. dxe4 cxd5 12. exd5 (12. exf5 $5 {Those of you, who wish to spend some extra time on independent study, might take a look at this move. According to GM Evgeny Postny, this could potentially give some attacking chances. However, I fully trust my silicon friend and its evaluation in this sharp position. According to the engine, Black enjoys a clear plus after relatively simple consolidating moves such as: Nxf5 , Qf6 and Bc5 / Bg7 .}) 12... Bg7 {In my opinion, this is the refutation of the 7.Ng5 move. White spent many moves attempting to open the position and start the attack with a queen and knights but eventually it is Black, who has a lead in development and relatively easy way to finish the opening stage of the game.} (12... Qa5+ $5 {A valid, but rather complicated alternative for Black according to the (very well-explored) theory.}) (12... Nc2+ $2 {Again, this move is just too greedy considering Black's vulnerable king in the centre. Since this line has absolutely no value for our repertoire, I will take the liberty to conclude that White's attack will develop faster than Black manages to develop his kingside.}) 13. Bc4 {The engine already gives Black a winning advantage.} (13. Bd3 $2 {Black has a clear way to get a significant advantage with simple moves.} h6 14. Kd1 hxg5 15. Re1+ Kf7 16. Qg3 Re8 17. Bxg5 Rxe1+ 18. Kxe1 Bf6 {Black had a significant material advantage and no apparent problems. 0-1 Felczer,K-Brauer, V/Hessen 1996 (33)}) ({The best move is} 13. Kd1 h6 14. Nf3 Nxf3 15. Qxd8+ Kxd8 16. gxf3 d6 17. f4 {How appealing is this? I would definitely not recommend going for such a position with White in what is supposed to be a course on an entertaining opening.1/2-1/2 Van der Weide,K-Timmermans,I/Sas van Gent 1996/EXT 98 (26)}) (13. Qg3 $2 {The purpose of this quiet move is to avoid the queens exchange, which could occur after black's h7 - h6 forcing the knight to retreat from g5 . However, according to GM Postny, Black has a clear way to the advantage now.} O-O {! That's the point. This move became possible, after the white queen has left the h4 square. Please note that with the queen on h4 , Qxh7 would lead to a checkmate.} 14. Bd3 ({(} 14. Bc4 $5 {Is also possible, but Black is fine after 14... b5} b5 {)}) ({(} 14. d6 {attempts to freeze the Black d pawn and prepares Bc4 ideas. However, Black organizes active play faster with: Qa5 / Re8 .)}) 14... Qa5+ 15. Bd2 Re8+ 16. Kd1 Qa4+ {It seems that Black has the better chances here, mainly due to the much safer position of his king.}) 13... h6 14. Qg3 hxg5 {This actually gives White a surprisingly dangerous initiative for the piece.} ({The most accurate move is probably} 14... b5 $1 {Black gains space in queenside and clears the way for the bishop on c8 .} 15. Bd3 hxg5 16. Bxg5 Bf6 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. O-O O-O {-+ Black simply enjoys a winning material advantage. 0-1 Barnsley,T-Kuhlmann,A/Internet 1998 (36)}) 15. Bxg5 Bf6 16. Bxf6 (16. d6 {This is an interesting attempt to open the light-squared bishop once more. Even though this position is outside of the scope of my proposed repertoire, it is worth remembering the d5 - d6 idea, as it could be used in various types of Belgrade Gambit positions.} Ne6 ({(Obviously not:} 16... Bxg5 $4 17. Qe5+ {White wins the rook on h8 and likely the game.} Ne6 18. Qxh8+ Kf7 19. Qh7+ {White maintains material equality and a promising attack against Black's exposed king.)}) 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. O-O Kf7 {Black still has a lot of work to do, but only he can win here.} 19. Rad1 Re8 20. Rfe1 b6 {White's attack pretty much evaporated. Black is going to gradually improve his position and likely convert the material bonus. Once the bishop is developed to b7 and the king place on g7 , White's hope is over.}) 16... Qxf6 17. O-O-O {The awkward placement of the Black knight and White's lead in development provide White with full compensation for the piece! However, let's remember that this position only occurred due to Black imprecise play.} Kf7 {Trying to silently walk away from the crime scene.} 18. Qe3 {The black knight is trapped in the centre.} b5 19. Bf1 {The only retreat to ensure capturing the knight in the next move.} Bb7 20. Rxd4 {White probably did not sense the danger.} (20. Qxd4 {Simply leads to an equal endgame. Technically, White is up a pawn but Black's pieces are just much more active. It seems dynamically balanced.}) 20... Rac8+ 21. Kd1 Rc5 {Black is a pawn down, but his counterattack is lethal.} 22. Qd2 Rhc8 23. Rd3 Qh4 {Threats, threats everywhere! Honestly, it looks like White played the Fischer Random for the first time.} 24. b4 Rc1+ 25. Qxc1 Rxc1+ 26. Kxc1 Qc4+ 27. Kd1 Qxa2 28. h4 Bxd5 {After this forcing sequence it's quite clear that White has a bad piece coordination with the rook and bishop on their initial positions. In the meantime, Black simply wants to grab a few pawns more (b4 or f2 ) and push the a&b tandem. Black's position is winning.} *

