{The game you're about to see presents simplicity of White's play on queenside in one of the typical Belgrade Gambit endgames. Please pay attention to the way White managed to restrict majority of Black's pieces and simply win the weak pawns.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nf6 {The Belgrade Gambit may also arise on the board through the Petroff.} 3. Nc3 Nc6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Nxd5 {As demonstrated in the theoretical section, the immediate capture on d5 is far from optimal.} 6. exd5 Bb4+ 7. Bd2 Qe7+ 8. Qe2 Bxd2+ 9. Kxd2 {This move the key move to getting a good position with White. As the queens are about to be exchanged, we no longer need to castle. It makes perfect sense to centralize the king in this peculiar way.} Qxe2+ 10. Bxe2 {White already has a much better position despite the pawn deficit.} Nb4 11. Bc4 (11. Rhe1 {This is my suggested move in the course. I believe it's a good improvement over the older 11.Bc4.}) 11... O-O {If playing normal moves is bad, then the overall position is most likely problematic. Apparently, this is just not fast enough as White manages to create typical strategic grip on the queenside. Let's take a look.} ({Better was} 11... b5 12. Bb3 Bb7 {Black's position is still much worse but playable.}) 12. a3 {White is in no rush to win the d4 pawn back. Instead, the objective is to drive the black knight to a worse position.} b5 {Black tries a delayed idea I advocated for a moment ago but it's too late.} (12... Na6 {Black is completely outplayed as there are no perspectives for the Black knight. Even if it temporarily gets to c5 , it will be pushed back with b2 - b4 .} 13. Rhe1 d6 14. Bxa6 $1 {This alternative ideas is exceptionally strong as White follows it up with Nxd4 and Re7 . The knight may easily occupy c6 outpost. Black will also suffer from his horrific pawns on a7 and a6 .} bxa6 15. Nxd4 {The engine claims White is winning here. Let's just agree on a significant advantage, which should be relatively easy to convert with active logical moves.}) 13. axb4 bxc4 14. Nxd4 {White has a decisive strategic advantage as Black's queenside pawn formation is just sad.} Bb7 15. Ra5 {The key move. The rook both protects the d5 pawn as well as attacks the one on a7 . White's next moves are Kc3 , Kxc4 and preparation for c2 - c4 strengthening the pawn on d5 .} a6 16. Kc3 Rae8 17. Kxc4 Re4 18. Kd3 Rfe8 19. c4 {Mission accomplished. Black has no real activity as the rooks have no clear purpose and the bishop is out of play.} f5 20. Rc5 c6 21. d6 {The Black bishop is a clear case of an isolated piece. Even stronger was} (21. Nxf5 cxd5 22. Nd6 {White will soon win even more material.}) 21... g6 22. f3 Re1 23. Rxe1 Rxe1 24. f4 {White prepares a transfer of the rook to e5 . The game is pretty much over when that happens as Black will be unable to prevent further infiltration.} Kf8 25. Re5 Rd1+ 26. Ke3 Rc1 27. b3 Re1+ 28. Kd2 Rxe5 29. fxe5 {The rest is just a matter of time. The knight is obviously superior to the bishop.} c5 30. bxc5 Bxg2 31. b4 f4 32. b5 a5 33. c6 Ke8 34. b6 {Black resigned as it's impossible to stop the b pawn.} *

