{The essence of the Belgrade Gambit will be presented in this game so fasten your seatbelts!} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Be7 6. Bc4 O-O 7. O-O Nxe4 8. Re1 Nf6 {As presented in the chapter dedicated to 5.. .Be7 and the Hector-Haubro game, 9... Nxe7 is considered the best, with 2 interesting directions later on.} 9. Rxe7 {Before the computer era, people used to get away with any sacrfice! I don't approve it but it's certainly fun.} Nxd5 {It was necessary to play} (9... Nxe7 10. Nxf6+ gxf6 11. Bh6 Re8 12. Qxd4 d5 {Black manages to parry the attack. For instance} 13. Qxf6 $2 {A bit too optimistic.} Nf5 {All of the sudden, Black takes over the initiative.}) 10. Rxf7 {Is this rook vaccinated?! Somebody stop it! Eric Prie was one of the afficionados of the Belgrade Gambit and he presented great resourcefullnes in his games.} Rxf7 11. Bxd5 {White will regain the material soon with great attacking chances.} h6 12. Nxd4 d6 {much better was} (12... Qe7 {protecting the rook on f7}) (12... Qf6 {After this move, Black could at least take back with the queen.}) 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bxf7+ Kxf7 15. Qh5+ Kg8 16. Bxh6 {Effectively, Black can't take the bishop, so White wins a pawn.} Be6 (16... gxh6 $4 {Black really shouldn't invite the enemy's army any closer.} 17. Qg6+ Kh8 18. Qxh6+ Kg8 19. Qg6+ Kh8 20. Re1 Bd7 21. Qh6+ Kg8 22. Re3 {Black will soon face some serious shelling. Most likely, it will be a winning attack.}) 17. Bd2 Qd7 18. Re1 Rf8 19. Bc3 {White maintains annoying pressure. If we combine it with a pawn advantage and a healthier pawn structure, it becomes evident that White is heading for a win.} Rf7 20. Re4 Bf5 21. Rh4 {Threatening mate on h8 .} Kf8 22. Qh8+ Ke7 23. Qa8 {An interesting queen transfer. Now the a7 pawn could be taken. The queen also vacates the h8 square for the rook.} Qe6 24. Rh8 Qd7 25. Qxa7 c5 26. Qb8 Bxc2 27. Bxg7 {I'm not sure what happened here, but White blundered a bishop.} Ke6 {Black missed a second chance.} (27... Rxg7 28. Qf8+ Ke6 29. Rh6+ Kd5 {As scary as it may be, Black is not losing directly and the bishop is gone. Black is objectively slightly better here, but obviously the position is very complex.}) 28. Bc3 Qc6 29. Qe8+ Qxe8 30. Rxe8+ {White made a very practical decision of transforming the attack into a winning endgame.} Kd7 31. Rg8 d5 32. Rg7 {Even if you play the Belgrade Gambit, you need to be open to winning in the endgame. I'm really sorry about that but you will not always get to give a checkmate. It's actually written in Chessable's terms and conditions.} Ke6 33. Rxf7 Kxf7 34. Kf1 {Preventing the d pawn from getting dangerously close to promotion.} d4 35. Ba5 c6 36. Bb6 Ke6 37. Bxc5 {With such a huge material advantage, the rest is a piece of cake.} Kd5 38. Ba7 c5 39. Ke2 Bb1 40. a3 c4 41. Kd2 Be4 42. f3 Bf5 43. h4 Bg6 44. g4 {At last, the White passed pawns started going forward and White won deservedly.} *

