[PlyCount "107"]

{The line chosen by the legendary Swedish player, GM Jonny Hector is an interesting alternative to what I propose in the course. Feel free to test it along with the lines I recommend.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 Be7 6. Bc4 O-O 7. O-O Nxe4 8. Re1 Nf6 {We have reached one of those positions in the course where White is unable to get full material equality. That's the price for those mighty bishops, I guess.} 9. Nxe7+ Nxe7 10. Qxd4 d5 11. Bd3 Ng6 {In my humble opinion, this is the best continuation for Black in the 5... Be7 line. There may be other lines with good evaluation but this one is simple and logical for players of all levels.} 12. b4 {It may look odd at first glance. Why would White start playing on queenside all of the sudden? As you see, the queen on d4 is exceptionally active. However, Black could be interested in playing something like b7 - b6 followed by c7 - c5 driving the queen away from its active post. Thus, White secures the control over the c5 square in advance. The dark-squared bishop is most probably going to be developed via b2 in order to create pressure along the long diagonal. However, the g5 square is also available. This is not a forcing continuation. Instead, White tries to restrict Black to the extent possible.} (12. Bg5 {This is my recommendation for this course but I fully understand the idea chosen by GM Hector. It's also one of the top lines of the engine.}) 12... c6 (12... Qd6 {This is stronger according to the engine. Black could simply play Bd7 connecting the rooks and preparing Rae8 or Rfe8 .}) 13. a4 {White tries to push the a pawn to a5 to ensure full control over the dark squares on queenside.} Qb6 {Now White is allowed to take over the initiative. much better was} (13... Bg4 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Rxe5 Bh5 {Preparing Bg6 to exchange the bishops.}) 14. Qxb6 axb6 15. Be3 Bg4 (15... Nd7 {It protects the pawn but completely shuts down the bishop.} 16. c3 {White has full compensation for the pawn due to the more active pieces as well as a healthier pawn structure.}) 16. Bxb6 Bxf3 17. gxf3 {White managed to restore the material equality at the cost of the kingside pawn formation.} Rfe8 18. Bxg6 {Clearly a bad strategic decision. Perhaps White got afraid of Ne5 / Nf4 ideas but there was no need for such drastic measures. White should have tried the more active} (18. Rxe8+ Rxe8 19. b5 {trying to open the queenside and possibly create a passed pawn there.}) 18... hxg6 19. Rxe8+ Rxe8 20. Kf1 {Centralization of the king is usually a good idea in the ending.} Nd7 21. Bd4 {The bishop is much stronger than the knight. White should open the queenside to create pawn weaknesses in Black's position.} f6 22. a5 Kf7 23. b5 {Interesting idea. GM Hector tries to create a passed pawn using a small tactical trick.} c5 {Another line was:} (23... cxb5 24. Rb1 Ra8 25. Rxb5 Ke6 {Black should manage to hold equality.}) 24. Be3 Ra8 25. Bf4 Ne5 26. Ke2 Nc4 27. a6 bxa6 28. bxa6 {White managed to get a very strong passed pawn on a6 . Will this be enough for a win?} g5 29. Bc7 {Another inaccuracy. While it seems logical to keep the bishop close to the pawn, the bishop will now be attacked by Black, getting quicker access to the passed a pawn. better was} (29. Bg3) 29... Ke6 30. a7 d4 {Not a good idea. Black should have defended more passively. Much better was:} (30... Kd7 31. Bb8 Ne5 {Black is about to play Nc6 winning the a pawn.}) 31. Ra6+ Kd5 32. Bb8 {GM Hector allows the opponent to equalize once more. A study-like continuation was necessary in order to get good winning chances.} (32. Kd1 Nb2+ 33. Kd2 Nc4+ 34. Kc1 {After the triangulation Black runs out of logical moves.} Ne5 35. Rd6+ {Now White regroups his rook and bishop.} Kc4 36. Bb6 Kb5 37. Rd8 {White wins material.}) 32... Ne5 33. Rb6 Nc6 34. Rb7 Kc4 35. Kd2 Kd5 36. Kd3 Nb4+ 37. Kd2 Nc6 {No progress for White.} 38. c3 Kc4 39. cxd4 Kxd4 40. Kc2 Kc4 {White is unable to create any practical problems to Black even though the pawn is close to promotion.} 41. h3 f5 42. Kd2 {The rest is not interesting.} f4 43. Kc2 Kd4 44. Kd2 Kc4 45. Ke2 Kd4 46. Kf1 Kc4 47. Kg2 Kd4 48. Kf1 Kc4 49. Ke1 Kd4 50. Kd1 Kd3 51. Rd7+ Kc4 52. Rb7 Kd3 53. Rd7+ Kc4 54. Rb7 {A draw was agreed. Even though White chose a calmer setup, Black quickly found himself in a tricky position. Eventually, White missed a few chances to get a decisive advantage and allowed the advantage to slip away.} *

